WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.313 align:middle line:84%
[SQUEAKING]
[RUSTLING] [CLICKING]

00:00:05.313 --> 00:00:11.688 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.688 --> 00:00:12.480 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: OK.

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:13.380 align:middle line:90%
So hi, everyone.

00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:17.460 align:middle line:84%
I'm Pablo, I'm teaching
Larry's lecturer this week.

00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:20.840 align:middle line:84%
I hope we are all here to
learn about prediction theory.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:24.040 align:middle line:84%
The plan for this week is to
talk about Bourgain's prediction

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:27.160 align:middle line:84%
theorem, which is an
extremely important theorem

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:30.840 align:middle line:84%
with applications in many
areas of mathematics, including

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:33.120 align:middle line:84%
some pretty striking
recent ones.

00:00:33.120 --> 00:00:37.680 align:middle line:84%
And I think Larry has told
you at least a bit about it.

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:40.440 align:middle line:84%
Well, we won't be able to
do a full proof because it

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:42.000 align:middle line:90%
would take way too long.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.292 align:middle line:84%
But what I'm going
to do is explain--

00:00:45.292 --> 00:00:48.000 align:middle line:84%
OK, so you've seen the analog of
this theorem in the finite field

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:48.520 align:middle line:90%
setting.

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:52.920 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to state it again
to so as our starting point.

00:00:52.920 --> 00:00:55.640 align:middle line:84%
And then the plan is
to go through the steps

00:00:55.640 --> 00:00:57.720 align:middle line:84%
in the strategy in the
finite field setting

00:00:57.720 --> 00:01:02.210 align:middle line:84%
and see what goes wrong and
what are the ideas that one uses

00:01:02.210 --> 00:01:05.530 align:middle line:90%
to overcome what goes wrong.

00:01:05.530 --> 00:01:10.450 align:middle line:84%
OK, so recall how this theorem
looks like in the finite field

00:01:10.450 --> 00:01:11.110 align:middle line:90%
setting.

00:01:11.110 --> 00:01:16.330 align:middle line:84%
And by finite field, I mean
prime finite field, prime order,

00:01:16.330 --> 00:01:19.770 align:middle line:84%
because otherwise,
it's not true.

00:01:19.770 --> 00:01:21.650 align:middle line:84%
The statement was,
hopefully, something

00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:31.923 align:middle line:84%
like this, given t between 0
and 2 and s between 0 and 1.

00:01:31.923 --> 00:01:34.650 align:middle line:84%
t, I want it to
be neither 0 nor 2

00:01:34.650 --> 00:01:36.450 align:middle line:84%
because there wouldn't
be anything to say.

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:38.150 align:middle line:90%
s has to be positive.

00:01:38.150 --> 00:01:40.010 align:middle line:90%
Could be 1.

00:01:40.010 --> 00:01:46.130 align:middle line:84%
There exists some epsilon that
depends on these two parameters

00:01:46.130 --> 00:01:51.930 align:middle line:84%
and is positive with the
following properties.

00:01:51.930 --> 00:01:59.180 align:middle line:84%
If X is in Fp squared
and has size p to the s.

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:03.020 align:middle line:84%
So s dimensional
set in some sense.

00:02:03.020 --> 00:02:08.740 align:middle line:84%
And D is a set of directions,
let's say a subset of p.

00:02:08.740 --> 00:02:14.620 align:middle line:84%
And it has size p to
the t, so dimension t.

00:02:14.620 --> 00:02:24.860 align:middle line:84%
Then so I use the notation pi
theta of X to be the projection.

00:02:24.860 --> 00:02:28.020 align:middle line:84%
And we can write the projection
in this way, I guess,

00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:31.340 align:middle line:90%
just x1 plus theta x2.

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:34.780 align:middle line:90%
So from Fp squared to Fp.

00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:39.940 align:middle line:90%
Then we can find a--

00:02:39.940 --> 00:02:43.860 align:middle line:84%
sorry, I messed up the
parameters already.

00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:48.580 align:middle line:84%
So the size of X is between
p to the 0 and p squared,

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:49.907 align:middle line:90%
and t is between 0 and 2.

00:02:49.907 --> 00:02:50.740 align:middle line:90%
So this should be t.

00:02:50.740 --> 00:02:52.020 align:middle line:90%
This should be s.

00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:52.700 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:57.520 align:middle line:84%
Then there is a "large,"
between quotes, projection.

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:04.120 align:middle line:84%
Then the maximum over
theta in D of the size

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:08.600 align:middle line:84%
of the projection
of X is at least

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:11.760 align:middle line:90%
p to the t over 22 plus epsilon.

00:03:11.760 --> 00:03:14.480 align:middle line:84%
So we're getting an
epsilon over t over 2.

00:03:14.480 --> 00:03:17.980 align:middle line:84%
And p to the t over 2 is
the obvious lower bound.

00:03:17.980 --> 00:03:21.040 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to come back
to this obvious lower bound

00:03:21.040 --> 00:03:23.200 align:middle line:90%
in a minute.

00:03:23.200 --> 00:03:25.220 align:middle line:84%
In fact, there is
a stronger version.

00:03:25.220 --> 00:03:27.320 align:middle line:84%
I think you proved
this in detail,

00:03:27.320 --> 00:03:31.200 align:middle line:84%
and you discussed
the stronger version.

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:34.360 align:middle line:84%
So let me state the stronger
version because, well, first

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:36.920 align:middle line:84%
of all, it's important in
itself for applications

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:38.535 align:middle line:84%
of the finite
field result. But I

00:03:38.535 --> 00:03:40.910 align:middle line:84%
would say it's even more
important in the Euclidean case.

00:03:40.910 --> 00:03:43.920 align:middle line:90%


00:03:43.920 --> 00:03:45.760 align:middle line:84%
Not only we can
find-- so this says

00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:48.580 align:middle line:84%
we can find the direction so
that the projection is large,

00:03:48.580 --> 00:03:50.640 align:middle line:90%
the projection of the whole set.

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:54.130 align:middle line:84%
But moreover, we can
find the direction,

00:03:54.130 --> 00:03:57.010 align:middle line:84%
so that if we project
any dense subset of X,

00:03:57.010 --> 00:03:59.610 align:middle line:90%
the projection is still large.

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:02.990 align:middle line:84%
So if we take the maximum
over now the minimum--

00:04:02.990 --> 00:04:06.570 align:middle line:84%
so we look at the worst
possible subset which is dense.

00:04:06.570 --> 00:04:10.450 align:middle line:84%
So we take the minimum
over subsets of X

00:04:10.450 --> 00:04:16.370 align:middle line:84%
which are dense in the sense
that they have relative density

00:04:16.370 --> 00:04:17.500 align:middle line:90%
p to the minus epsilon.

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:20.490 align:middle line:90%


00:04:20.490 --> 00:04:24.450 align:middle line:84%
And then we look at
the projection of Y.

00:04:24.450 --> 00:04:27.050 align:middle line:84%
So we try to make the projection
of a dense subset of X

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:28.390 align:middle line:90%
as small as possible.

00:04:28.390 --> 00:04:32.770 align:middle line:84%
But we can't even if we have
this additional robustness

00:04:32.770 --> 00:04:36.130 align:middle line:84%
of looking at all
subsets of Y, we still

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:38.030 align:middle line:90%
have a gain over t over 2.

00:04:38.030 --> 00:04:41.530 align:middle line:90%


00:04:41.530 --> 00:04:45.050 align:middle line:84%
So this is Bourgain's
projection theorem

00:04:45.050 --> 00:04:46.280 align:middle line:90%
in the finite field setting.

00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:51.250 align:middle line:90%


00:04:51.250 --> 00:04:53.200 align:middle line:84%
And you have proved
at least this version,

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:55.440 align:middle line:84%
and I think discussed
this version.

00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:57.240 align:middle line:84%
If anything I say
is not correct,

00:04:57.240 --> 00:05:00.380 align:middle line:84%
or if I say something that
you are not familiar with

00:05:00.380 --> 00:05:04.980 align:middle line:84%
or you don't understand
anything, please just ask.

00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:06.900 align:middle line:90%
So now we want to--

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:10.340 align:middle line:84%
OK, so before moving
to the Euclidean case,

00:05:10.340 --> 00:05:15.660 align:middle line:84%
let me make this remark
on the trivial bound.

00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:19.540 align:middle line:84%
So the trivial bound is
p to the t over 2 just

00:05:19.540 --> 00:05:22.200 align:middle line:90%
without the epsilon.

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:27.100 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem is not
true if we replace p

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:30.140 align:middle line:84%
by p squared or anything
which is not a prime.

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:32.660 align:middle line:84%
Because if you look at Fp
squared, for example, then

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:34.860 align:middle line:90%
Fp is sitting there.

00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:42.340 align:middle line:84%
And if we take f to be Xp and D
to be Fp sitting in Fp squared,

00:05:42.340 --> 00:05:49.780 align:middle line:84%
we don't escape Fp because Fp
is a f So this is not true.

00:05:49.780 --> 00:05:52.470 align:middle line:84%
But without the epsilon,
it's true in any field,

00:05:52.470 --> 00:05:55.270 align:middle line:90%
and the argument is trivial.

00:05:55.270 --> 00:05:57.568 align:middle line:84%
OK, so one should never
use the word "trivial,"

00:05:57.568 --> 00:05:58.860 align:middle line:90%
but I will use it in this case.

00:05:58.860 --> 00:06:02.805 align:middle line:90%


00:06:02.805 --> 00:06:04.930 align:middle line:84%
So everything is trivial
once you've understood it.

00:06:04.930 --> 00:06:07.055 align:middle line:84%
And nothing is trivial
before you've understood it.

00:06:07.055 --> 00:06:09.460 align:middle line:84%
But I will still use
the word "trivial" here.

00:06:09.460 --> 00:06:13.030 align:middle line:90%


00:06:13.030 --> 00:06:15.390 align:middle line:84%
So if D has at
least two elements--

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:16.610 align:middle line:90%
so same setting as above.

00:06:16.610 --> 00:06:19.350 align:middle line:84%
So if D has more
than one element,

00:06:19.350 --> 00:06:21.490 align:middle line:84%
so let's allow p to the
s where s is positive,

00:06:21.490 --> 00:06:28.230 align:middle line:84%
just two elements, then
the maximum over theta in D

00:06:28.230 --> 00:06:38.390 align:middle line:84%
of the projection of X is at
least the size of X to the 1/2.

00:06:38.390 --> 00:06:41.190 align:middle line:84%
So if the size of
X is p to the t

00:06:41.190 --> 00:06:43.190 align:middle line:84%
would be at least
p to the t over 2.

00:06:43.190 --> 00:06:45.150 align:middle line:84%
And again, we will
see that this doesn't

00:06:45.150 --> 00:06:48.760 align:middle line:90%
use the factor p is prime.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:50.920 align:middle line:90%
So it's much more general.

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:53.160 align:middle line:84%
This is trivial because
just take two elements.

00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:54.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:55.220 align:middle line:90%
Again, trivial.

00:06:55.220 --> 00:06:56.300 align:middle line:90%
I will explain it.

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:57.900 align:middle line:84%
And then once you've
understood it,

00:06:57.900 --> 00:07:03.340 align:middle line:84%
you will agree that it's
trivial OK, so know that.

00:07:03.340 --> 00:07:04.540 align:middle line:90%
So just take two elements.

00:07:04.540 --> 00:07:06.960 align:middle line:84%
So D has at least
two elements by--

00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:12.400 align:middle line:84%
so let's just take two elements,
phi times theta prime in D.

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:14.160 align:middle line:84%
So the observation
that makes this trivial

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:23.120 align:middle line:84%
is that if you map X to the
projection in direction theta

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:27.000 align:middle line:84%
comma the projection in
direction theta prime--

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.730 align:middle line:84%
so this is small X, an
element of Xp squared.

00:07:30.730 --> 00:07:33.920 align:middle line:90%


00:07:33.920 --> 00:07:35.960 align:middle line:90%
This is injective.

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:40.160 align:middle line:84%
So we can recover a vector
from two projections

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:41.030 align:middle line:90%
by linear algebra.

00:07:41.030 --> 00:07:47.970 align:middle line:90%


00:07:47.970 --> 00:07:52.290 align:middle line:84%
So this means that the
image of X under this map

00:07:52.290 --> 00:07:55.910 align:middle line:90%
has size at least the domain.

00:07:55.910 --> 00:07:59.170 align:middle line:84%
Because you have
injective map, the image

00:07:59.170 --> 00:08:01.570 align:middle line:90%
has the size of the domain.

00:08:01.570 --> 00:08:04.770 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this implies
that the size of X

00:08:04.770 --> 00:08:07.330 align:middle line:84%
is at least the size of
the projection in direction

00:08:07.330 --> 00:08:15.370 align:middle line:84%
theta of X times the size of the
projection in direction theta

00:08:15.370 --> 00:08:15.952 align:middle line:90%
prime.

00:08:15.952 --> 00:08:18.410 align:middle line:84%
So at least one of these two
has to be at least square root

00:08:18.410 --> 00:08:23.730 align:middle line:90%
of the size of X.

00:08:23.730 --> 00:08:26.953 align:middle line:84%
So this is the proof
of the trivial bound.

00:08:26.953 --> 00:08:28.870 align:middle line:84%
And I hope you will agree
that it's very easy.

00:08:28.870 --> 00:08:30.850 align:middle line:90%
And it uses literally nothing.

00:08:30.850 --> 00:08:33.150 align:middle line:84%
Well, it uses that
this map is injective,

00:08:33.150 --> 00:08:34.519 align:middle line:90%
but this is a very general fact.

00:08:34.519 --> 00:08:38.289 align:middle line:90%


00:08:38.289 --> 00:08:41.770 align:middle line:84%
In particular, this is
true on any finite field.

00:08:41.770 --> 00:08:43.110 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't have to be prime.

00:08:43.110 --> 00:08:45.550 align:middle line:84%
But for this, we
need it to be prime.

00:08:45.550 --> 00:08:48.950 align:middle line:84%
So now we want to have
a Euclidean version

00:08:48.950 --> 00:08:52.510 align:middle line:90%
of this statement.

00:08:52.510 --> 00:08:53.670 align:middle line:90%
And we will see that--

00:08:53.670 --> 00:08:58.910 align:middle line:84%
OK, so maybe let's discuss
the Euclidean setting.

00:08:58.910 --> 00:09:01.230 align:middle line:84%
So I will start with
the setting, which

00:09:01.230 --> 00:09:03.990 align:middle line:84%
is the way in which
Euclidean setting has

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:05.670 align:middle line:90%
appeared in this course before.

00:09:05.670 --> 00:09:09.630 align:middle line:84%
But then I will rescale things
to a setting that I like better.

00:09:09.630 --> 00:09:11.650 align:middle line:84%
But let's start
with the following.

00:09:11.650 --> 00:09:15.950 align:middle line:84%
So we have a parameter R, which
is the scale, or maybe 1 over R

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:18.870 align:middle line:90%
is the scale.

00:09:18.870 --> 00:09:25.110 align:middle line:84%
And then we have our set X is
contained in the ball of radius

00:09:25.110 --> 00:09:27.110 align:middle line:84%
R. Let's say centered
at the origin

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:30.310 align:middle line:84%
or really any ball of radius R.
It doesn't make any difference.

00:09:30.310 --> 00:09:34.740 align:middle line:84%
And let's suppose that X
is a union of unit balls.

00:09:34.740 --> 00:09:39.470 align:middle line:90%


00:09:39.470 --> 00:09:43.680 align:middle line:90%
And D, let's say in 0, 1.

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:46.060 align:middle line:84%
Maybe 1, 2 would be
slightly more natural,

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:49.080 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't really
matter much, is a 1 over R

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:49.990 align:middle line:90%
separated set.

00:09:49.990 --> 00:09:55.520 align:middle line:90%


00:09:55.520 --> 00:09:57.460 align:middle line:84%
OK, so D is a finite
set of directions.

00:09:57.460 --> 00:10:00.760 align:middle line:84%
They are separated by
the scale 1 over R.

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:04.120 align:middle line:84%
And X is a unit of
unit balls in BR.

00:10:04.120 --> 00:10:06.260 align:middle line:84%
So we measure X by
Lebesgue measure.

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:09.400 align:middle line:84%
We measure D by cardinality
and use bars in both cases.

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:14.120 align:middle line:84%
I think this is the convention
you'll be using in this course.

00:10:14.120 --> 00:10:18.640 align:middle line:84%
And well, we would
like the following.

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:20.060 align:middle line:90%
Well, we would like that, right?

00:10:20.060 --> 00:10:25.400 align:middle line:84%
So except that now X is not
in Fp squared, but in BR,

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:28.840 align:middle line:84%
and D is no longer
in Fp but in 0, 1.

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:30.380 align:middle line:90%
So pi theta is still the same.

00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:37.050 align:middle line:84%
So pi theta of x1, x2
is x1 plus theta x2.

00:10:37.050 --> 00:10:39.680 align:middle line:90%


00:10:39.680 --> 00:10:41.510 align:middle line:84%
We could look at
orthogonal projections

00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:46.350 align:middle line:84%
but up to a reparametrization
is actually easier to work with.

00:10:46.350 --> 00:10:47.310 align:middle line:90%
It's not important.

00:10:47.310 --> 00:10:49.660 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we can ask,
Does the same happen?

00:10:49.660 --> 00:10:52.890 align:middle line:90%


00:10:52.890 --> 00:10:55.790 align:middle line:84%
So just all the bars mean
different things now.

00:10:55.790 --> 00:10:58.130 align:middle line:84%
So when we project
X, we are looking

00:10:58.130 --> 00:11:01.050 align:middle line:84%
at the measure, the big measure
one-dimensional Lebesgue measure

00:11:01.050 --> 00:11:03.130 align:middle line:90%
of the image, and so on.

00:11:03.130 --> 00:11:06.330 align:middle line:84%
So do we have any hope of
proving the same theorem

00:11:06.330 --> 00:11:09.090 align:middle line:90%
in this generality?

00:11:09.090 --> 00:11:10.590 align:middle line:90%
So does anyone want to guess?

00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:13.480 align:middle line:84%
Could this theorem be
true in this setting?

00:11:13.480 --> 00:11:16.250 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: No, it's not
true because the balls are

00:11:16.250 --> 00:11:22.610 align:middle line:84%
closely packed into kind
of a ball of radius blue R.

00:11:22.610 --> 00:11:23.770 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: OK.

00:11:23.770 --> 00:11:24.270 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:11:24.270 --> 00:11:25.690 align:middle line:90%
That's a great example.

00:11:25.690 --> 00:11:28.930 align:middle line:84%
But that great example, then
I will come back to this,

00:11:28.930 --> 00:11:31.250 align:middle line:84%
still satisfies
the trivial bound.

00:11:31.250 --> 00:11:36.730 align:middle line:84%
So can the trivial bound happen
in this setting as written?

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:40.340 align:middle line:84%
Because, yeah, if everything
is packed into a smaller

00:11:40.340 --> 00:11:43.960 align:middle line:84%
ball, if you project, you
still have an interval of size

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:45.100 align:middle line:90%
the square root.

00:11:45.100 --> 00:11:46.720 align:middle line:90%
So you're right, that fails.

00:11:46.720 --> 00:11:48.500 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to come
back to your example.

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:50.580 align:middle line:84%
That fails, but
this still holds.

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:53.020 align:middle line:84%
Can the trivial bound
be true in this setting

00:11:53.020 --> 00:11:54.600 align:middle line:90%
without assuming anything else?

00:11:54.600 --> 00:12:02.340 align:middle line:90%


00:12:02.340 --> 00:12:05.780 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do you see how
only two interactions are--

00:12:05.780 --> 00:12:07.460 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: OK.

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:09.780 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, two directions
maybe is asking too much.

00:12:09.780 --> 00:12:11.460 align:middle line:90%
Let's say there are--

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:12.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:12.420 --> 00:12:14.680 align:middle line:84%
What is p to the t,
and what is p to the s?

00:12:14.680 --> 00:12:17.060 align:middle line:84%
It would be rho to the
t, and rho to the s.

00:12:17.060 --> 00:12:20.220 align:middle line:84%
Not rho, R-- R to
the t, R to the s.

00:12:20.220 --> 00:12:22.120 align:middle line:84%
Let's say there are R
to the s directions.

00:12:22.120 --> 00:12:24.180 align:middle line:90%
Let's make it a little bit more.

00:12:24.180 --> 00:12:27.160 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, with two
directions maybe--

00:12:27.160 --> 00:12:27.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:27.660 --> 00:12:30.460 align:middle line:84%
Let's say there are R to
the s directions, which

00:12:30.460 --> 00:12:32.660 align:middle line:90%
R1 over R2 separated.

00:12:32.660 --> 00:12:33.910 align:middle line:90%
Can the trivial bound hold?

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:36.550 align:middle line:90%


00:12:36.550 --> 00:12:38.790 align:middle line:84%
OK, what is an
example of a set that

00:12:38.790 --> 00:12:40.650 align:middle line:90%
has one very small projection?

00:12:40.650 --> 00:12:43.773 align:middle line:90%


00:12:43.773 --> 00:12:45.190 align:middle line:84%
So what is a set
in the plane that

00:12:45.190 --> 00:12:47.230 align:middle line:90%
has one very small projection?

00:12:47.230 --> 00:12:49.470 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Called
the Gaussian line?

00:12:49.470 --> 00:12:50.830 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: A line.

00:12:50.830 --> 00:12:53.430 align:middle line:84%
OK, you cannot literally be
a line because it's a union

00:12:53.430 --> 00:12:54.010 align:middle line:90%
of balls.

00:12:54.010 --> 00:12:56.910 align:middle line:84%
But we put the balls
in a long segment.

00:12:56.910 --> 00:13:06.230 align:middle line:84%
So an example that should make
us kind of scared is a 1 times

00:13:06.230 --> 00:13:08.150 align:middle line:90%
R rectangle.

00:13:08.150 --> 00:13:12.470 align:middle line:84%
So we pack with balls in this
way as someone suggested.

00:13:12.470 --> 00:13:15.550 align:middle line:84%
Then if we project
literally down,

00:13:15.550 --> 00:13:19.270 align:middle line:84%
we get something of size 1,
which is much, much, much less

00:13:19.270 --> 00:13:21.150 align:middle line:90%
than square root of R.

00:13:21.150 --> 00:13:26.722 align:middle line:84%
But if we perturb the vertical
projection by R to the s,

00:13:26.722 --> 00:13:30.190 align:middle line:84%
the projection will
have size R to the s.

00:13:30.190 --> 00:13:33.510 align:middle line:84%
And if s is less than 1/2, it
will be less than square root

00:13:33.510 --> 00:13:39.310 align:middle line:84%
of R. So instead of
projecting in this direction,

00:13:39.310 --> 00:13:42.730 align:middle line:84%
if we project in a nearby
direction, this is still bad.

00:13:42.730 --> 00:13:47.420 align:middle line:90%
So if this is X and--

00:13:47.420 --> 00:13:52.330 align:middle line:90%


00:13:52.330 --> 00:13:53.182 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:53.182 --> 00:13:56.610 align:middle line:84%
So I think actually,
I chose a bad--

00:13:56.610 --> 00:13:59.298 align:middle line:84%
so this projection cannot
be written in this way.

00:13:59.298 --> 00:14:01.590 align:middle line:84%
Oh yes, it can be written in
this way, just theta is 0.

00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:04.850 align:middle line:84%
It can be very well
written in this way.

00:14:04.850 --> 00:14:09.770 align:middle line:84%
If theta is, let's
say, minus R to the s,

00:14:09.770 --> 00:14:15.210 align:middle line:84%
R to the s, then
the projection of X

00:14:15.210 --> 00:14:20.690 align:middle line:84%
will have size of the
order of R to the s.

00:14:20.690 --> 00:14:24.730 align:middle line:84%
Well, s could be positive
but less than 1/2.

00:14:24.730 --> 00:14:28.025 align:middle line:90%
So this is very bad.

00:14:28.025 --> 00:14:30.600 align:middle line:90%
So we don't want--

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:31.350 align:middle line:90%
this is not theta.

00:14:31.350 --> 00:14:34.600 align:middle line:90%
This is D. So this is very bad.

00:14:34.600 --> 00:14:38.500 align:middle line:84%
So we don't want D to
look like an interval

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:41.860 align:middle line:84%
or to be very concentrated in an
interval or something like this.

00:14:41.860 --> 00:14:45.900 align:middle line:84%
So we want to avoid
such a situation.

00:14:45.900 --> 00:14:47.700 align:middle line:90%
So this is bad.

00:14:47.700 --> 00:14:51.740 align:middle line:84%
It makes even the trivial
estimate hopeless.

00:14:51.740 --> 00:14:54.680 align:middle line:84%
So maybe we'll come back to this
if there is time, maybe not.

00:14:54.680 --> 00:14:57.900 align:middle line:84%
But maybe as an
exercise for you,

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:01.200 align:middle line:84%
not exercise for
marks or anything,

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:02.960 align:middle line:90%
but you can think of it.

00:15:02.960 --> 00:15:03.980 align:middle line:90%
Not now.

00:15:03.980 --> 00:15:04.920 align:middle line:90%
Now, pay attention.

00:15:04.920 --> 00:15:06.302 align:middle line:90%
But you can think later.

00:15:06.302 --> 00:15:07.760 align:middle line:84%
What goes wrong
with this argument?

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:09.983 align:middle line:84%
Because in R2, it's still
true that two projections,

00:15:09.983 --> 00:15:11.400 align:middle line:84%
even if the angles
are very close,

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:15.180 align:middle line:90%
determine the original vector.

00:15:15.180 --> 00:15:18.700 align:middle line:90%
So how is this compatible?

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:20.180 align:middle line:90%
So you can think about this.

00:15:20.180 --> 00:15:22.950 align:middle line:84%
And then you will
understand many of the--

00:15:22.950 --> 00:15:24.940 align:middle line:84%
well, not many, one of
one of the important

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:27.460 align:middle line:84%
reasons why things are
much more complicated

00:15:27.460 --> 00:15:30.100 align:middle line:90%
in this Euclidean world.

00:15:30.100 --> 00:15:30.792 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:30.792 --> 00:15:35.910 align:middle line:84%
So now suppose that we
avoid this in some way.

00:15:35.910 --> 00:15:38.910 align:middle line:84%
Can we have a hope of
having the theorem?

00:15:38.910 --> 00:15:41.750 align:middle line:84%
And the answer, as
you said, is still no.

00:15:41.750 --> 00:15:45.030 align:middle line:84%
So this is one example we
should be worried about.

00:15:45.030 --> 00:15:52.190 align:middle line:84%
Here is another example we
should be worried about, where

00:15:52.190 --> 00:15:56.610 align:middle line:84%
X is, essentially, let's say a
ball of radius square root of R.

00:15:56.610 --> 00:16:00.230 align:middle line:84%
It can be really any radius
between 0 and 1, but just to--

00:16:00.230 --> 00:16:03.050 align:middle line:84%
so X should be a union
of disjoint unit balls.

00:16:03.050 --> 00:16:07.150 align:middle line:84%
So we just pack, in
a very dense way,

00:16:07.150 --> 00:16:13.310 align:middle line:84%
unit balls in a ball
of radius R to the 1/2.

00:16:13.310 --> 00:16:19.510 align:middle line:84%
So the volume of X the
area of X is roughly R.

00:16:19.510 --> 00:16:21.990 align:middle line:84%
But if we project it
in any direction--

00:16:21.990 --> 00:16:26.110 align:middle line:84%
so we have to get rid
of bad sets like this.

00:16:26.110 --> 00:16:28.280 align:middle line:84%
But let's get rid of
bad sets like this

00:16:28.280 --> 00:16:29.530 align:middle line:90%
in the strongest possible way.

00:16:29.530 --> 00:16:32.120 align:middle line:84%
Let's suppose that
D is everything.

00:16:32.120 --> 00:16:36.760 align:middle line:84%
So here, we are focusing on
what can go wrong with X. So

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:39.400 align:middle line:90%
let D be absolutely everything.

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:44.080 align:middle line:84%
Well, here, every projection is
going to be a segment of length

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:47.400 align:middle line:90%
roughly R to the 1/2.

00:16:47.400 --> 00:16:51.960 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at
the projection of X,

00:16:51.960 --> 00:16:57.120 align:middle line:84%
this has size roughly square
root of the size of X.

00:16:57.120 --> 00:16:59.590 align:middle line:90%
And this is for every theta.

00:16:59.590 --> 00:17:06.720 align:middle line:90%


00:17:06.720 --> 00:17:09.839 align:middle line:84%
So in fact, if you avoid
this in a suitable way,

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:13.720 align:middle line:84%
we recover the trivial bound,
but it is no longer trivial.

00:17:13.720 --> 00:17:15.520 align:middle line:84%
Maybe we'll come back
to this on Thursday

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:17.500 align:middle line:84%
depending on how we
are doing with time.

00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:19.720 align:middle line:84%
So the trivial bound is
no longer trivial even

00:17:19.720 --> 00:17:21.359 align:middle line:90%
in the best case.

00:17:21.359 --> 00:17:24.720 align:middle line:84%
But if we want to go
beyond the trivial bound,

00:17:24.720 --> 00:17:26.800 align:middle line:84%
we also need to assume
something about X.

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:30.190 align:middle line:84%
So we need to avoid this,
and we need to avoid this.

00:17:30.190 --> 00:17:33.450 align:middle line:84%
And you see that in both
cases, what's going on--

00:17:33.450 --> 00:17:36.310 align:middle line:84%
so the geometric
picture is different.

00:17:36.310 --> 00:17:41.650 align:middle line:84%
But in both cases,
D is an interval.

00:17:41.650 --> 00:17:42.810 align:middle line:90%
X is a ball.

00:17:42.810 --> 00:17:46.050 align:middle line:84%
So we want to avoid D
looking like an interval or X

00:17:46.050 --> 00:17:47.610 align:middle line:90%
looking like a box.

00:17:47.610 --> 00:17:49.890 align:middle line:84%
If we do that in a
suitable way, then we

00:17:49.890 --> 00:17:54.270 align:middle line:84%
can indeed get a
similar statement.

00:17:54.270 --> 00:17:55.830 align:middle line:90%
So let me actually state it.

00:17:55.830 --> 00:18:04.690 align:middle line:90%


00:18:04.690 --> 00:18:06.970 align:middle line:84%
OK, let me say that
Bourgain didn't state it

00:18:06.970 --> 00:18:07.920 align:middle line:90%
in this way, but--

00:18:07.920 --> 00:18:14.390 align:middle line:90%


00:18:14.390 --> 00:18:16.380 align:middle line:90%
it follows from what he proved.

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:19.540 align:middle line:90%


00:18:19.540 --> 00:18:22.990 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that-- same
setting as before.

00:18:22.990 --> 00:18:33.150 align:middle line:90%


00:18:33.150 --> 00:18:35.240 align:middle line:90%
So we are still assuming this.

00:18:35.240 --> 00:18:38.860 align:middle line:90%


00:18:38.860 --> 00:18:41.980 align:middle line:84%
Would have been faster to just
write everything down again.

00:18:41.980 --> 00:18:44.180 align:middle line:84%
OK, but we need to
add some assumptions

00:18:44.180 --> 00:18:45.970 align:middle line:90%
to avoid these bad examples.

00:18:45.970 --> 00:18:49.580 align:middle line:90%


00:18:49.580 --> 00:18:51.920 align:middle line:84%
OK, so first of all, we
need some quantifiers.

00:18:51.920 --> 00:18:57.540 align:middle line:90%
So given 0, t.

00:18:57.540 --> 00:19:03.380 align:middle line:84%
So t is strictly between 0
and 2 and s larger than 0.

00:19:03.380 --> 00:19:05.240 align:middle line:90%
There exist now two parameters.

00:19:05.240 --> 00:19:07.040 align:middle line:84%
So I could do with
one parameter.

00:19:07.040 --> 00:19:09.420 align:middle line:84%
So you see that even
here, I'm using epsilon

00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:10.780 align:middle line:90%
for two different things--

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:13.740 align:middle line:84%
for the growth and for
the robustness in passing

00:19:13.740 --> 00:19:14.680 align:middle line:90%
two subsets.

00:19:14.680 --> 00:19:17.420 align:middle line:84%
Here, I'm going to use two
different letters because they

00:19:17.420 --> 00:19:21.780 align:middle line:90%
denote different things.

00:19:21.780 --> 00:19:27.120 align:middle line:84%
So there exists epsilon and
eta, both, depending on s and t,

00:19:27.120 --> 00:19:32.740 align:middle line:84%
and both positive such
that the following holds.

00:19:32.740 --> 00:19:36.160 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that we have
X union of unit balls

00:19:36.160 --> 00:19:41.340 align:middle line:84%
in the R, 1 over R
separated set of directions.

00:19:41.340 --> 00:19:44.342 align:middle line:90%


00:19:44.342 --> 00:19:46.800 align:middle line:84%
And then we need to assume
something because otherwise it's

00:19:46.800 --> 00:19:47.720 align:middle line:90%
not true.

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:51.480 align:middle line:84%
So we need to assume that X
and D are not very concentrated

00:19:51.480 --> 00:19:53.960 align:middle line:84%
in small balls or
small intervals.

00:19:53.960 --> 00:19:56.840 align:middle line:84%
So this is what we
are going to assume.

00:19:56.840 --> 00:20:03.760 align:middle line:84%
If we intersect X with
any ball of radius r,

00:20:03.760 --> 00:20:06.680 align:middle line:84%
we see only a small piece
of X And the smaller they

00:20:06.680 --> 00:20:08.360 align:middle line:90%
are, the smaller the piece.

00:20:08.360 --> 00:20:11.060 align:middle line:84%
The range of this little
r is between 1 and big R,

00:20:11.060 --> 00:20:12.560 align:middle line:84%
because X is a
union of unit balls,

00:20:12.560 --> 00:20:14.960 align:middle line:90%
and it's a subset of the R ball.

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:18.440 align:middle line:84%
So this should be less
than or equal than what?

00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:20.480 align:middle line:84%
Well, on the one hand,
we want to compare this

00:20:20.480 --> 00:20:23.610 align:middle line:84%
to the natural
scale, which is R.

00:20:23.610 --> 00:20:27.610 align:middle line:84%
So this tells us how much
smaller the reference scale is

00:20:27.610 --> 00:20:29.730 align:middle line:90%
compared to the global scale.

00:20:29.730 --> 00:20:34.550 align:middle line:84%
And let's put the t here, which
is motivated by the fact that--

00:20:34.550 --> 00:20:35.050 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:35.050 --> 00:20:38.230 align:middle line:90%


00:20:38.230 --> 00:20:47.450 align:middle line:84%
So X has area R to the t And
D has cardinality R to the s.

00:20:47.450 --> 00:20:49.150 align:middle line:90%
This t matches this t.

00:20:49.150 --> 00:20:53.530 align:middle line:90%


00:20:53.530 --> 00:20:55.570 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to have the size of X.

00:20:55.570 --> 00:20:59.250 align:middle line:84%
So this is saying if R is
much smaller than big R--

00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:02.250 align:middle line:84%
so if R is big R,
we have all of X.

00:21:02.250 --> 00:21:06.290 align:middle line:84%
So we cannot get any gain
because X is contained

00:21:06.290 --> 00:21:09.570 align:middle line:84%
in the ball of radius R. But
if we are intersecting X with

00:21:09.570 --> 00:21:15.690 align:middle line:84%
a smaller ball, we
have a big decay,

00:21:15.690 --> 00:21:22.380 align:middle line:84%
sort of power decay with respect
to-- so only a very small part

00:21:22.380 --> 00:21:26.580 align:middle line:84%
of X can be in a small ball
compared to the whole of X.

00:21:26.580 --> 00:21:29.020 align:middle line:84%
It turns out that it's very
important for applications

00:21:29.020 --> 00:21:30.860 align:middle line:90%
to have some leeway here.

00:21:30.860 --> 00:21:35.580 align:middle line:84%
And this leeway is given
by this parameter eta.

00:21:35.580 --> 00:21:39.140 align:middle line:84%
So this leeway says
that actually, we

00:21:39.140 --> 00:21:44.860 align:middle line:84%
don't need to assume anything if
little r is very close to big R.

00:21:44.860 --> 00:21:48.140 align:middle line:84%
Because if r is
very close to big R,

00:21:48.140 --> 00:21:49.600 align:middle line:84%
this will still
be bigger than 1,

00:21:49.600 --> 00:21:52.540 align:middle line:84%
and then we have a
trivial inequality.

00:21:52.540 --> 00:21:56.020 align:middle line:84%
So this is saying the
global scales don't matter.

00:21:56.020 --> 00:21:56.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:56.940 --> 00:22:01.510 align:middle line:84%
A very similar story with
D. If we intersect D--

00:22:01.510 --> 00:22:05.000 align:middle line:84%
OK, both here are intervals,
but I'm going to--

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.860 align:middle line:90%


00:22:07.860 --> 00:22:09.620 align:middle line:90%
steal the notation for balls.

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:10.760 align:middle line:90%
This is at most.

00:22:10.760 --> 00:22:14.820 align:middle line:84%
Again, we have our
leeway R to the epsilon.

00:22:14.820 --> 00:22:17.940 align:middle line:90%
And then rho is between 0 and 1.

00:22:17.940 --> 00:22:24.190 align:middle line:84%
So here, the right thing to
write is rho to the s times--

00:22:24.190 --> 00:22:26.690 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the size of X
is actually R to the t.

00:22:26.690 --> 00:22:28.490 align:middle line:84%
But still, I want to
write it in this way

00:22:28.490 --> 00:22:31.870 align:middle line:84%
so it's clear that when we
intersect with the ball,

00:22:31.870 --> 00:22:37.790 align:middle line:84%
we are seeing only a small piece
of X. And the same thing here.

00:22:37.790 --> 00:22:40.590 align:middle line:84%
OK, so these are the
conditions that we

00:22:40.590 --> 00:22:44.590 align:middle line:84%
impose to avoid these
bad counterexamples.

00:22:44.590 --> 00:22:46.250 align:middle line:84%
You could say that
they are overkill.

00:22:46.250 --> 00:22:48.830 align:middle line:84%
And we are avoiding
not only this but--

00:22:48.830 --> 00:22:49.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:49.750 --> 00:22:52.310 align:middle line:84%
Put it in a different way,
there is a whole universe

00:22:52.310 --> 00:22:53.910 align:middle line:90%
between this and this.

00:22:53.910 --> 00:22:54.940 align:middle line:90%
And, yeah, this is true.

00:22:54.940 --> 00:22:56.690 align:middle line:84%
In fact, these conditions
can be weakened.

00:22:56.690 --> 00:22:58.950 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I will make some
remark about this.

00:22:58.950 --> 00:23:01.110 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so these
are the assumptions.

00:23:01.110 --> 00:23:05.327 align:middle line:90%
Then there exists one direction.

00:23:05.327 --> 00:23:06.910 align:middle line:84%
And once there is
one direction, there

00:23:06.910 --> 00:23:12.350 align:middle line:84%
are many directions, such that
we have the same conclusion.

00:23:12.350 --> 00:23:19.640 align:middle line:90%


00:23:19.640 --> 00:23:25.240 align:middle line:84%
So if we look at the infimum
over all dense subsets--

00:23:25.240 --> 00:23:29.460 align:middle line:84%
and "dense" means with
respect to this parameter eta.

00:23:29.460 --> 00:23:31.100 align:middle line:84%
So eta is like a
tolerance parameter.

00:23:31.100 --> 00:23:34.190 align:middle line:84%
It gives us some leeway at
different places to play with.

00:23:34.190 --> 00:23:40.040 align:middle line:90%


00:23:40.040 --> 00:23:44.560 align:middle line:84%
So Y is a dense subset of X
with this leeway R to the minus

00:23:44.560 --> 00:23:46.200 align:middle line:90%
epsilon.

00:23:46.200 --> 00:23:52.280 align:middle line:84%
Then we project the subset,
and we get the gain.

00:23:52.280 --> 00:23:56.570 align:middle line:84%
So the "trivial" now is
no longer trivial but sort

00:23:56.570 --> 00:23:57.580 align:middle line:90%
of natural.

00:23:57.580 --> 00:23:58.900 align:middle line:90%
Lower bound is t over 2.

00:23:58.900 --> 00:24:00.430 align:middle line:90%
And we beat it by epsilon.

00:24:00.430 --> 00:24:03.600 align:middle line:90%


00:24:03.600 --> 00:24:04.560 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:09.357 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Does Y also have
to be a union of unit balls?

00:24:09.357 --> 00:24:11.190 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: That's
a very good question.

00:24:11.190 --> 00:24:14.940 align:middle line:90%


00:24:14.940 --> 00:24:16.680 align:middle line:90%
I don't think so.

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:18.820 align:middle line:90%
But, yeah, just in case, yes.

00:24:18.820 --> 00:24:21.080 align:middle line:90%
Just in case I'm too tired, yes.

00:24:21.080 --> 00:24:23.660 align:middle line:90%


00:24:23.660 --> 00:24:24.160 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:25.000 align:middle line:90%
Let's say yes.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:26.060 align:middle line:90%
Let's say yes.

00:24:26.060 --> 00:24:28.780 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to restate
this in a different language

00:24:28.780 --> 00:24:31.920 align:middle line:84%
soon, where we will
get rid of balls.

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:36.605 align:middle line:84%
But, yeah, let's say Y is
also union of unit balls

00:24:36.605 --> 00:24:38.480 align:middle line:84%
So you see that there
are lots of parameters.

00:24:38.480 --> 00:24:39.960 align:middle line:84%
It's kind of a
technical statement.

00:24:39.960 --> 00:24:41.377 align:middle line:84%
The assumption
looks a bit strange

00:24:41.377 --> 00:24:42.980 align:middle line:84%
if you have never
seen this before,

00:24:42.980 --> 00:24:46.540 align:middle line:84%
but nevertheless is, again,
an extremely important theorem

00:24:46.540 --> 00:24:50.500 align:middle line:84%
with an unbelievable
range of applications.

00:24:50.500 --> 00:24:52.820 align:middle line:84%
We keep discovering
applications.

00:24:52.820 --> 00:24:55.180 align:middle line:84%
Something which is also
important to remark

00:24:55.180 --> 00:24:57.140 align:middle line:84%
is that all the
applications really use

00:24:57.140 --> 00:25:00.460 align:middle line:90%
the statement as a black box.

00:25:00.460 --> 00:25:04.180 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes people also get
inspired by the proof.

00:25:04.180 --> 00:25:06.820 align:middle line:84%
But it's not a situation
where the proof gets used,

00:25:06.820 --> 00:25:08.940 align:middle line:90%
really the statement gets used.

00:25:08.940 --> 00:25:11.468 align:middle line:84%
So it's a very, very
powerful statement.

00:25:11.468 --> 00:25:13.510 align:middle line:84%
And I guess in the rest
of the course with Larry,

00:25:13.510 --> 00:25:18.030 align:middle line:84%
you will see some of the ways
in which it is very powerful.

00:25:18.030 --> 00:25:19.630 align:middle line:90%
How does one prove this?

00:25:19.630 --> 00:25:23.230 align:middle line:84%
By the way, I'm going to,
as I say, sketch the proof,

00:25:23.230 --> 00:25:25.950 align:middle line:84%
skipping pretty
much all details.

00:25:25.950 --> 00:25:28.790 align:middle line:84%
But the proof I'm going to
sketch is not Bourgain's proof.

00:25:28.790 --> 00:25:35.470 align:middle line:84%
It's maybe a new proof
that I'm writing together

00:25:35.470 --> 00:25:38.520 align:middle line:84%
with Hong Wang that takes
ideas from different places.

00:25:38.520 --> 00:25:42.110 align:middle line:90%


00:25:42.110 --> 00:25:44.110 align:middle line:84%
So it's not Bourgain's
original proof.

00:25:44.110 --> 00:25:47.110 align:middle line:90%


00:25:47.110 --> 00:25:49.350 align:middle line:84%
The general scheme
will follow the steps

00:25:49.350 --> 00:25:51.830 align:middle line:84%
that you've seen in the
finite field setting,

00:25:51.830 --> 00:25:55.110 align:middle line:84%
but there are very
significant challenges.

00:25:55.110 --> 00:25:57.750 align:middle line:84%
So what I'm going to do is
go over each of the steps

00:25:57.750 --> 00:25:59.870 align:middle line:84%
and explain what
the challenges are

00:25:59.870 --> 00:26:02.030 align:middle line:90%
and what can one do to fix them.

00:26:02.030 --> 00:26:05.030 align:middle line:84%
And then you will have to
trust me that, indeed, they

00:26:05.030 --> 00:26:05.968 align:middle line:90%
can be fixed.

00:26:05.968 --> 00:26:07.260 align:middle line:90%
So I won't go into the details.

00:26:07.260 --> 00:26:10.550 align:middle line:90%


00:26:10.550 --> 00:26:17.240 align:middle line:84%
Before doing so, you saw that if
you want to go from finite field

00:26:17.240 --> 00:26:22.320 align:middle line:84%
to Euclidean settings,
sometimes you

00:26:22.320 --> 00:26:25.760 align:middle line:84%
have to add more assumptions,
otherwise things fail

00:26:25.760 --> 00:26:27.807 align:middle line:90%
because of some easy examples.

00:26:27.807 --> 00:26:29.140 align:middle line:90%
But this is not always the case.

00:26:29.140 --> 00:26:33.880 align:middle line:84%
So there are some statements
in the finite setting that

00:26:33.880 --> 00:26:39.380 align:middle line:84%
extend a pretty straightforward
way to this Euclidean setting.

00:26:39.380 --> 00:26:43.720 align:middle line:84%
So in order to do
this, I'm going

00:26:43.720 --> 00:26:49.900 align:middle line:84%
to change the language a little
bit and maybe rescale this.

00:26:49.900 --> 00:26:55.000 align:middle line:84%
So instead of looking at unions
of unit balls in the R ball,

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:56.960 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to look at--

00:26:56.960 --> 00:27:00.760 align:middle line:84%
so basically, I need to rescale
the set down by 1 over R.

00:27:00.760 --> 00:27:03.520 align:middle line:84%
So X is going to live
in the unit ball.

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:06.440 align:middle line:84%
And then it will be a
union of 1 over R balls.

00:27:06.440 --> 00:27:09.870 align:middle line:84%
And of course, if you
rescale you scale,

00:27:09.870 --> 00:27:12.050 align:middle line:84%
you have to scale everywhere
else in the statement.

00:27:12.050 --> 00:27:16.810 align:middle line:84%
But instead of looking at
the volume of the set X,

00:27:16.810 --> 00:27:19.170 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to use the
delta-covering number.

00:27:19.170 --> 00:27:22.250 align:middle line:84%
For the directions, instead of
assuming that they are disjoint,

00:27:22.250 --> 00:27:24.390 align:middle line:84%
I'm also going to use
delta-covering number.

00:27:24.390 --> 00:27:25.730 align:middle line:90%
So I bring both--

00:27:25.730 --> 00:27:27.530 align:middle line:84%
so basically X and
D, I want to use

00:27:27.530 --> 00:27:32.610 align:middle line:84%
the same language and same scale
to make things more homogeneous.

00:27:32.610 --> 00:27:38.930 align:middle line:84%
So let me spend a couple
of minutes talking

00:27:38.930 --> 00:27:40.650 align:middle line:90%
about delta-covering number.

00:27:40.650 --> 00:27:44.550 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that X is a subset
of really any metric space,

00:27:44.550 --> 00:27:49.210 align:middle line:90%
but let's say Rd, then--

00:27:49.210 --> 00:27:54.970 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is, I'm guessing,
definition or notation X bar

00:27:54.970 --> 00:27:56.010 align:middle line:90%
delta.

00:27:56.010 --> 00:28:02.090 align:middle line:84%
So bar with the subscript
delta is the smallest.

00:28:02.090 --> 00:28:16.600 align:middle line:84%
number of delta balls needed
to cover X. Could be infinite,

00:28:16.600 --> 00:28:19.660 align:middle line:84%
but in all this
business, we are only

00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:22.240 align:middle line:84%
looking at bounded sets, in
which case this is finite.

00:28:22.240 --> 00:28:24.540 align:middle line:84%
So everything we
are going to see

00:28:24.540 --> 00:28:27.900 align:middle line:90%
is going to be a finite number.

00:28:27.900 --> 00:28:31.720 align:middle line:84%
Basically, our measuring
resolution is delta.

00:28:31.720 --> 00:28:34.460 align:middle line:84%
We cannot distinguish anything
that happens under scale delta.

00:28:34.460 --> 00:28:37.290 align:middle line:84%
So this is a natural way of
measuring the size of the set.

00:28:37.290 --> 00:28:40.420 align:middle line:90%


00:28:40.420 --> 00:28:42.920 align:middle line:84%
Just a definition, but
some observations--

00:28:42.920 --> 00:28:45.900 align:middle line:90%


00:28:45.900 --> 00:28:50.500 align:middle line:84%
well, the first one I think
I should never use the word

00:28:50.500 --> 00:28:54.140 align:middle line:84%
"trivial," but I hope I'm
justified in saying that this is

00:28:54.140 --> 00:29:00.980 align:middle line:84%
trivial if X is, to
make it really trivial,

00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:09.630 align:middle line:84%
2 delta separated, then the
delta-covering number is just

00:29:09.630 --> 00:29:12.950 align:middle line:84%
the cardinality, because
for each point in the set,

00:29:12.950 --> 00:29:14.130 align:middle line:90%
we need a different ball.

00:29:14.130 --> 00:29:17.750 align:middle line:90%


00:29:17.750 --> 00:29:21.070 align:middle line:84%
So this will be the case for D.
D is delta separated, but delta

00:29:21.070 --> 00:29:22.950 align:middle line:90%
separated, 2 delta separated.

00:29:22.950 --> 00:29:24.510 align:middle line:90%
Doesn't make a big difference.

00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:26.270 align:middle line:84%
So if the set is
delta separated,

00:29:26.270 --> 00:29:29.850 align:middle line:90%
it's morally just cardinality.

00:29:29.850 --> 00:29:43.710 align:middle line:84%
If X is a union of delta balls,
then the delta-covering number

00:29:43.710 --> 00:29:44.790 align:middle line:90%
is--

00:29:44.790 --> 00:29:48.250 align:middle line:84%
well, you use the
balls to cover the set.

00:29:48.250 --> 00:29:50.790 align:middle line:84%
You need to normalize to pass
between measure and counting

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:52.590 align:middle line:90%
how many balls there are.

00:29:52.590 --> 00:29:57.950 align:middle line:84%
So I think it should be
delta to the minus D.

00:29:57.950 --> 00:29:59.550 align:middle line:84%
So D is the ambient
dimension where

00:29:59.550 --> 00:30:05.410 align:middle line:84%
X leaves times the
Lebesgue measure of X.

00:30:05.410 --> 00:30:06.930 align:middle line:90%
Did I get this right?

00:30:06.930 --> 00:30:08.350 align:middle line:90%
It's not actually equal.

00:30:08.350 --> 00:30:09.510 align:middle line:90%
It's comparable.

00:30:09.510 --> 00:30:12.070 align:middle line:90%


00:30:12.070 --> 00:30:12.570 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:30:12.570 --> 00:30:14.862 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Afterward, does X
have to be a disjoint union

00:30:14.862 --> 00:30:16.057 align:middle line:90%
of delta balls?

00:30:16.057 --> 00:30:17.890 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: That's
a very good question.

00:30:17.890 --> 00:30:19.450 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:30:19.450 --> 00:30:24.370 align:middle line:84%
It's easier to believe if it is
a disjoint union of delta balls.

00:30:24.370 --> 00:30:26.890 align:middle line:84%
And it is also true if
it's a non-disjoint union

00:30:26.890 --> 00:30:27.845 align:middle line:90%
of delta balls.

00:30:27.845 --> 00:30:29.970 align:middle line:84%
The reason is that if you
have a non-disjoint union

00:30:29.970 --> 00:30:34.030 align:middle line:84%
of delta balls, you can cover
it by finitely overlapping.

00:30:34.030 --> 00:30:36.790 align:middle line:84%
OK, if you have a disjoint
union of delta balls--

00:30:36.790 --> 00:30:39.130 align:middle line:84%
I hope this is clear, because
the best way to cover it

00:30:39.130 --> 00:30:42.450 align:middle line:90%
by using those balls.

00:30:42.450 --> 00:30:46.590 align:middle line:84%
If you have a finite overlapping
collection of delta balls, then

00:30:46.590 --> 00:30:50.890 align:middle line:84%
you just cover by defining the
overlapping family and you lose.

00:30:50.890 --> 00:30:54.250 align:middle line:84%
Any union of balls, you can
cover by finitely overlapping.

00:30:54.250 --> 00:30:55.690 align:middle line:84%
So I guess you
need some covering

00:30:55.690 --> 00:30:59.410 align:middle line:90%
theorem to make it precise.

00:30:59.410 --> 00:31:01.630 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, it's true, and we
are not going to use it.

00:31:01.630 --> 00:31:03.520 align:middle line:84%
But you can convince
yourself that it's true.

00:31:03.520 --> 00:31:07.820 align:middle line:84%
Again, easier to believe if the
balls are disjoint, but also

00:31:07.820 --> 00:31:09.212 align:middle line:90%
true if the balls are disjoint.

00:31:09.212 --> 00:31:10.920 align:middle line:84%
It's equal if the
balls are not disjoint.

00:31:10.920 --> 00:31:11.963 align:middle line:90%
There is a wiggle.

00:31:11.963 --> 00:31:14.380 align:middle line:84%
In fact, the wiggle, I guess,
maybe depends on the ambient

00:31:14.380 --> 00:31:18.660 align:middle line:90%
dimension D.

00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:22.620 align:middle line:84%
I'm just making these remarks
to explain how this relates

00:31:22.620 --> 00:31:23.722 align:middle line:90%
to our previous setting.

00:31:23.722 --> 00:31:26.180 align:middle line:84%
Because now, from now on, we're
going to measure everything

00:31:26.180 --> 00:31:28.140 align:middle line:90%
by the delta-covering number.

00:31:28.140 --> 00:31:29.700 align:middle line:84%
The point I want to
make is that this

00:31:29.700 --> 00:31:33.380 align:middle line:84%
recovers the volume and
the cardinality when

00:31:33.380 --> 00:31:36.080 align:middle line:84%
the sets are delta-separated
or union of delta balls.

00:31:36.080 --> 00:31:41.380 align:middle line:90%


00:31:41.380 --> 00:31:43.940 align:middle line:84%
Another way of thinking
about delta-covering-number

00:31:43.940 --> 00:31:45.760 align:middle line:90%
is as a box-counting number.

00:31:45.760 --> 00:31:55.420 align:middle line:84%
So let D delta be the
covering of D by delta cubes.

00:31:55.420 --> 00:32:03.910 align:middle line:90%
So this is delta k plus 0 delta.

00:32:03.910 --> 00:32:06.070 align:middle line:84%
Maybe let's make it
half open so that this

00:32:06.070 --> 00:32:13.430 align:middle line:84%
is a partition to the d,
where k is in Z to the d.

00:32:13.430 --> 00:32:17.550 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just doing
a dyadic covering.

00:32:17.550 --> 00:32:20.590 align:middle line:84%
Delta doesn't have to
be dyadic, but I'm--

00:32:20.590 --> 00:32:24.550 align:middle line:90%
so this is-- how do you say?

00:32:24.550 --> 00:32:31.590 align:middle line:84%
The tiling of Rd by
cubes of size delta.

00:32:31.590 --> 00:32:33.670 align:middle line:84%
I make them half open
so they are disjoint,

00:32:33.670 --> 00:32:36.670 align:middle line:90%
but it's not very important

00:32:36.670 --> 00:32:46.790 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the delta-covering
number is up to a multiplicative

00:32:46.790 --> 00:32:50.390 align:middle line:84%
constant, the number of
cubes in the delta that

00:32:50.390 --> 00:32:51.340 align:middle line:90%
are hit by the set.

00:32:51.340 --> 00:32:53.950 align:middle line:90%


00:32:53.950 --> 00:32:58.840 align:middle line:84%
So the cardinality of
the cubes in D delta

00:32:58.840 --> 00:33:02.680 align:middle line:90%
which intersect the set.

00:33:02.680 --> 00:33:06.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is why this is called
box counting number as well.

00:33:06.420 --> 00:33:09.040 align:middle line:90%


00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:12.000 align:middle line:84%
Why is this true
is because if you

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:15.260 align:middle line:84%
cover by cubes in
an efficient way--

00:33:15.260 --> 00:33:17.660 align:middle line:84%
so if you know how many
cubes you are hitting, well,

00:33:17.660 --> 00:33:21.720 align:middle line:84%
you can cover each cube by
a finite number of balls

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:24.840 align:middle line:90%
of radius delta.

00:33:24.840 --> 00:33:26.920 align:middle line:84%
Again, this wiggle
may depend on d.

00:33:26.920 --> 00:33:28.380 align:middle line:90%
So d is a fixed parameter.

00:33:28.380 --> 00:33:31.420 align:middle line:84%
It will be 1 or 2 for
protection theorem.

00:33:31.420 --> 00:33:32.900 align:middle line:90%
So I consider it as a constant.

00:33:32.900 --> 00:33:35.400 align:middle line:84%
So you can cover
each of these cubes

00:33:35.400 --> 00:33:39.000 align:middle line:84%
by a finite number of
delta balls and vice versa.

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:41.920 align:middle line:84%
If you have a delta
ball, you can cover it

00:33:41.920 --> 00:33:46.960 align:middle line:90%
by a finite number of cubes.

00:33:46.960 --> 00:33:52.080 align:middle line:84%
So that's the proof,
proof by picture.

00:33:52.080 --> 00:33:54.600 align:middle line:84%
One nice consequence of
this is that this allows

00:33:54.600 --> 00:33:57.810 align:middle line:90%
us to snap any set to a grid.

00:33:57.810 --> 00:34:01.450 align:middle line:84%
And then this allows us to
apply Euclidean-- not Euclidean,

00:34:01.450 --> 00:34:02.630 align:middle line:90%
integer results.

00:34:02.630 --> 00:34:04.130 align:middle line:90%
Discrete results.

00:34:04.130 --> 00:34:14.770 align:middle line:84%
So let's define-- so what is
X superscript bracket delta?

00:34:14.770 --> 00:34:19.230 align:middle line:84%
It's the set that is obtained
by snapping points to the grid.

00:34:19.230 --> 00:34:24.850 align:middle line:84%
So if X intersects this
cube, then this point

00:34:24.850 --> 00:34:27.969 align:middle line:90%
will be in X delta.

00:34:27.969 --> 00:34:30.130 align:middle line:84%
And this way, I snap
it to the lattice.

00:34:30.130 --> 00:34:30.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:30.630 --> 00:34:37.170 align:middle line:84%
Formally, this is all the
case such that the cube delta

00:34:37.170 --> 00:34:50.610 align:middle line:84%
k plus 0 delta to
the d intersects X.

00:34:50.610 --> 00:34:55.870 align:middle line:84%
So anytime that we see something
here, we look at this point.

00:34:55.870 --> 00:35:02.350 align:middle line:84%
And then because of this,
the delta-covering number

00:35:02.350 --> 00:35:05.310 align:middle line:84%
is roughly up to a
multiplicative constant,

00:35:05.310 --> 00:35:06.650 align:middle line:90%
the same as the cardinality.

00:35:06.650 --> 00:35:08.910 align:middle line:90%
This is now a finite set.

00:35:08.910 --> 00:35:11.510 align:middle line:90%
It's a finite set in a lattice.

00:35:11.510 --> 00:35:14.130 align:middle line:90%
So it's not just the lattice.

00:35:14.130 --> 00:35:17.010 align:middle line:84%
It's just the integer
lattice scaled down by delta,

00:35:17.010 --> 00:35:18.810 align:middle line:84%
but it's just the
integer lattice.

00:35:18.810 --> 00:35:21.790 align:middle line:90%


00:35:21.790 --> 00:35:29.190 align:middle line:84%
By using this, one can extend
many results that are true EZD

00:35:29.190 --> 00:35:30.840 align:middle line:90%
to delta-covering numbers.

00:35:30.840 --> 00:35:37.070 align:middle line:90%


00:35:37.070 --> 00:35:45.470 align:middle line:84%
So using this, in particular,
the following three things,

00:35:45.470 --> 00:35:47.910 align:middle line:84%
which are three
very important tools

00:35:47.910 --> 00:35:51.070 align:middle line:84%
in the proof of the finite field
case of recurrence projection

00:35:51.070 --> 00:35:54.400 align:middle line:84%
theorem and also in
the Euclidean case,

00:35:54.400 --> 00:35:56.300 align:middle line:90%
the Ruzsa triangle inequality.

00:35:56.300 --> 00:36:02.440 align:middle line:90%


00:36:02.440 --> 00:36:11.580 align:middle line:84%
The Plunnecke-Ruzsa
inequalities.

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:17.960 align:middle line:90%


00:36:17.960 --> 00:36:20.230 align:middle line:84%
And the Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers
theorem.

00:36:20.230 --> 00:36:31.400 align:middle line:90%


00:36:31.400 --> 00:36:35.260 align:middle line:84%
They all hold for delta-covering
numbers by putting bar there.

00:36:35.260 --> 00:36:38.480 align:middle line:84%
So when you see
bar, you put delta.

00:36:38.480 --> 00:36:41.560 align:middle line:84%
You use multiplicative
constants because of this.

00:36:41.560 --> 00:36:44.220 align:middle line:84%
So where you have equality,
you no longer have equality.

00:36:44.220 --> 00:36:45.750 align:middle line:90%
But this is very harmless.

00:36:45.750 --> 00:36:57.370 align:middle line:90%


00:36:57.370 --> 00:36:59.930 align:middle line:84%
For example, I'm going to
state that Ruzsa triangle

00:36:59.930 --> 00:37:01.190 align:middle line:90%
inequality as a model.

00:37:01.190 --> 00:37:04.160 align:middle line:84%
And then you can imagine
how the other two behave.

00:37:04.160 --> 00:37:07.450 align:middle line:90%


00:37:07.450 --> 00:37:14.530 align:middle line:84%
So we have three sets in
the same Rd, let's say,

00:37:14.530 --> 00:37:18.050 align:middle line:84%
bounded to make sure that the
delta-covering number is finite.

00:37:18.050 --> 00:37:21.390 align:middle line:84%
Then let's see if
I get this right.

00:37:21.390 --> 00:37:24.050 align:middle line:90%
If not, you just let me know.

00:37:24.050 --> 00:37:24.742 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:24.742 --> 00:37:28.210 align:middle line:84%
In the original, so in the
discrete Ruzsa triangle

00:37:28.210 --> 00:37:29.870 align:middle line:84%
inequality, here
we have inequality.

00:37:29.870 --> 00:37:31.687 align:middle line:84%
Here, we have inequality
up to a constant.

00:37:31.687 --> 00:37:33.520 align:middle line:84%
So this is the only
thing we have to change.

00:37:33.520 --> 00:37:39.530 align:middle line:90%


00:37:39.530 --> 00:37:40.030 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:40.030 --> 00:37:41.390 align:middle line:90%
Did I get this right?

00:37:41.390 --> 00:37:44.330 align:middle line:90%
Is this the correct statement?

00:37:44.330 --> 00:37:45.757 align:middle line:90%
OK, so this is an example.

00:37:45.757 --> 00:37:48.090 align:middle line:84%
Just put delta, delta, delta,
delta, and change equality

00:37:48.090 --> 00:37:50.260 align:middle line:90%
by equality up to a constant.

00:37:50.260 --> 00:37:52.220 align:middle line:90%
And how do you prove this?

00:37:52.220 --> 00:37:58.300 align:middle line:90%
Well, you snap it to the grid.

00:37:58.300 --> 00:38:02.660 align:middle line:84%
You have to be a little
bit careful because you

00:38:02.660 --> 00:38:03.760 align:middle line:90%
can snap A to the grid.

00:38:03.760 --> 00:38:05.080 align:middle line:90%
You can snap B to the grid.

00:38:05.080 --> 00:38:08.620 align:middle line:84%
And then you can take A minus
B for the snapped versions.

00:38:08.620 --> 00:38:11.300 align:middle line:84%
That's not going to be exactly
the same as snapping a minus b

00:38:11.300 --> 00:38:12.500 align:middle line:90%
to the grid.

00:38:12.500 --> 00:38:15.700 align:middle line:84%
So there is something that
doesn't exactly commute,

00:38:15.700 --> 00:38:17.960 align:middle line:90%
but it almost commutes.

00:38:17.960 --> 00:38:19.900 align:middle line:90%
So almost commutes.

00:38:19.900 --> 00:38:21.580 align:middle line:90%
So I'm not going to--

00:38:21.580 --> 00:38:23.940 align:middle line:84%
another exercise is for
you to convince yourself

00:38:23.940 --> 00:38:26.440 align:middle line:90%
that this is true.

00:38:26.440 --> 00:38:30.220 align:middle line:84%
So you see that for
the projection theorem,

00:38:30.220 --> 00:38:32.420 align:middle line:84%
we really need to
impose assumptions

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:34.553 align:middle line:84%
if we want it to hold in
the Euclidean setting.

00:38:34.553 --> 00:38:35.720 align:middle line:90%
But this is not always true.

00:38:35.720 --> 00:38:38.300 align:middle line:84%
Here, we have three
very important tools.

00:38:38.300 --> 00:38:42.100 align:middle line:84%
They basically work
in the same way.

00:38:42.100 --> 00:38:49.790 align:middle line:84%
So now we can start
going over the steps

00:38:49.790 --> 00:38:54.510 align:middle line:84%
in the proof of the theorem, the
finite field setting and seeing

00:38:54.510 --> 00:38:58.030 align:middle line:84%
what the obstacles are and
what one can do to overcome

00:38:58.030 --> 00:39:02.150 align:middle line:84%
the obstacles if one wants to
follow the same scheme of proof

00:39:02.150 --> 00:39:03.670 align:middle line:90%
in the Euclidean setting.

00:39:03.670 --> 00:39:06.050 align:middle line:90%
Any questions so far?

00:39:06.050 --> 00:39:13.790 align:middle line:90%


00:39:13.790 --> 00:39:21.630 align:middle line:84%
In the finite
field setting, what

00:39:21.630 --> 00:39:23.710 align:middle line:90%
was the first step in the proof?

00:39:23.710 --> 00:39:30.190 align:middle line:84%
It was to prove expansion using
a polynomial for just one set.

00:39:30.190 --> 00:39:33.190 align:middle line:90%
So let's recall what this was.

00:39:33.190 --> 00:39:35.430 align:middle line:90%
So if we have A in Fp--

00:39:35.430 --> 00:39:38.810 align:middle line:84%
OK, I guess let's say
the quantifiers first.

00:39:38.810 --> 00:39:49.560 align:middle line:84%
So given S in 0, 1, there
exists an epsilon such

00:39:49.560 --> 00:39:51.320 align:middle line:90%
that the following holds.

00:39:51.320 --> 00:39:55.620 align:middle line:84%
If we have a subset
of our prime field--

00:39:55.620 --> 00:39:57.680 align:middle line:84%
so here, it has to
be a prime field.

00:39:57.680 --> 00:40:00.280 align:middle line:84%
These are ready fails if
it is not a prime field.

00:40:00.280 --> 00:40:04.320 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to come back to
this point several times.

00:40:04.320 --> 00:40:07.560 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that it has
size P to the s.

00:40:07.560 --> 00:40:11.440 align:middle line:90%
Then there exists a polynomial--

00:40:11.440 --> 00:40:15.860 align:middle line:84%
actually, there
exists a polynomial,

00:40:15.860 --> 00:40:20.040 align:middle line:84%
which is fixed for all s, for
all epsilon, and for all a.

00:40:20.040 --> 00:40:23.282 align:middle line:84%
It can be x1, x2,
x3 minus x4, x5, x6.

00:40:23.282 --> 00:40:25.240 align:middle line:84%
So that polynomial works,
but it doesn't really

00:40:25.240 --> 00:40:27.880 align:middle line:90%
matter which polynomial it is.

00:40:27.880 --> 00:40:35.540 align:middle line:84%
So let's call it Q. If we
apply Q to A, we get expansion.

00:40:35.540 --> 00:40:45.300 align:middle line:90%


00:40:45.300 --> 00:40:48.900 align:middle line:84%
OK, so I think what
you did with Larry

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:50.400 align:middle line:90%
gave the following polynomial.

00:40:50.400 --> 00:40:52.940 align:middle line:84%
But I think it was
clear from what

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:54.700 align:middle line:84%
you did with Larry
that this really

00:40:54.700 --> 00:40:57.100 align:middle line:84%
doesn't matter which polynomial
it is, as long as you

00:40:57.100 --> 00:40:58.700 align:middle line:90%
have some polynomial.

00:40:58.700 --> 00:41:00.860 align:middle line:84%
Because at a later
stage, one is going

00:41:00.860 --> 00:41:03.660 align:middle line:84%
to apply Plunnecke-Ruzsa to
bring down the polynomial

00:41:03.660 --> 00:41:06.500 align:middle line:84%
the simplest
possible polynomial.

00:41:06.500 --> 00:41:07.700 align:middle line:90%
So that was a later step.

00:41:07.700 --> 00:41:11.820 align:middle line:84%
At this step, any
polynomial works.

00:41:11.820 --> 00:41:15.300 align:middle line:84%
So this one works, but it's
not important, which one it is.

00:41:15.300 --> 00:41:17.540 align:middle line:90%
How did you prove this?

00:41:17.540 --> 00:41:23.660 align:middle line:84%
So we can see to what extent
things go wrong in the Euclidean

00:41:23.660 --> 00:41:27.740 align:middle line:84%
setting, and to what extent we
can recycle some of the ideas.

00:41:27.740 --> 00:41:28.850 align:middle line:90%
So idea of proof.

00:41:28.850 --> 00:41:33.940 align:middle line:90%


00:41:33.940 --> 00:41:36.100 align:middle line:84%
If I claim that you saw
something with Larry

00:41:36.100 --> 00:41:38.620 align:middle line:84%
and you didn't,
please let me know.

00:41:38.620 --> 00:41:41.540 align:middle line:84%
He told me and showed me
notes, but I could still

00:41:41.540 --> 00:41:43.350 align:middle line:90%
be wrong about something.

00:41:43.350 --> 00:41:45.950 align:middle line:84%
What was the idea of
proof behind these?

00:41:45.950 --> 00:41:50.110 align:middle line:84%
So one looks at,
maybe let's call it

00:41:50.110 --> 00:41:54.390 align:middle line:90%
X. A minus A over A minus A.

00:41:54.390 --> 00:41:57.330 align:middle line:90%
Here, we skip 0.

00:41:57.330 --> 00:41:59.550 align:middle line:90%
We don't want to divide by 0.

00:41:59.550 --> 00:42:02.150 align:middle line:84%
And then there are
two possibilities.

00:42:02.150 --> 00:42:11.470 align:middle line:84%
Either X is everything, and then
one can conclude in some way--

00:42:11.470 --> 00:42:12.630 align:middle line:90%
I know this is not--

00:42:12.630 --> 00:42:14.830 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to
recall how to do it.

00:42:14.830 --> 00:42:18.750 align:middle line:84%
The other possibility is
that X is not everything.

00:42:18.750 --> 00:42:25.190 align:middle line:84%
If it's not everything, there
exists some little X in X

00:42:25.190 --> 00:42:34.310 align:middle line:84%
such that X plus 1 is not in
X. Because it's not everything.

00:42:34.310 --> 00:42:37.193 align:middle line:90%
And then one can also conclude.

00:42:37.193 --> 00:42:38.610 align:middle line:84%
So in both cases,
one has to work.

00:42:38.610 --> 00:42:40.152 align:middle line:84%
I'm not saying it's
trivial, but this

00:42:40.152 --> 00:42:42.400 align:middle line:90%
was the structure of the proof.

00:42:42.400 --> 00:42:46.800 align:middle line:84%
These extremely innocent
step is what distinguishes

00:42:46.800 --> 00:42:49.600 align:middle line:90%
Fp from Fp squared.

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:51.220 align:middle line:84%
If you were working
in Fp squared,

00:42:51.220 --> 00:42:55.200 align:middle line:84%
we would not be able to do
this because Fp squared has

00:42:55.200 --> 00:42:58.360 align:middle line:90%
a subgroup which is Fp.

00:42:58.360 --> 00:43:02.080 align:middle line:84%
So you cannot escape
Fp by adding 1.

00:43:02.080 --> 00:43:08.040 align:middle line:84%
So this extremely
innocent adding plus 1,

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:20.780 align:middle line:84%
distinguishes Fp and
Fp squared, let's say.

00:43:20.780 --> 00:43:25.240 align:middle line:90%


00:43:25.240 --> 00:43:28.880 align:middle line:90%
We want to do something similar.

00:43:28.880 --> 00:43:36.080 align:middle line:84%
So let's say we have an A.
Well, first of all, it's

00:43:36.080 --> 00:43:38.600 align:middle line:84%
very likely that we will need
to assume something about A.

00:43:38.600 --> 00:43:41.058 align:middle line:84%
In fact, we need to assume
something about in the Euclidean

00:43:41.058 --> 00:43:44.610 align:middle line:84%
setting, because
if A is a segment,

00:43:44.610 --> 00:43:47.330 align:middle line:84%
like any polynomial
check, it doesn't grow.

00:43:47.330 --> 00:43:56.850 align:middle line:84%
So if X is 1, 1 plus R, 1,
1 plus delta to the 1 minus

00:43:56.850 --> 00:43:59.875 align:middle line:84%
t, something like this,
just a small segment,

00:43:59.875 --> 00:44:01.750 align:middle line:84%
if you add it to itself
multiplied by itself,

00:44:01.750 --> 00:44:03.125 align:middle line:84%
you get slightly
longer segments.

00:44:03.125 --> 00:44:04.410 align:middle line:90%
There is no real growth.

00:44:04.410 --> 00:44:08.490 align:middle line:84%
It's exactly the
same issue as we

00:44:08.490 --> 00:44:11.650 align:middle line:84%
had when we were
projecting an X which was

00:44:11.650 --> 00:44:13.490 align:middle line:90%
to concentrate in a large ball.

00:44:13.490 --> 00:44:15.910 align:middle line:84%
But now we know how
to get rid of that.

00:44:15.910 --> 00:44:19.770 align:middle line:84%
We need to assume that A
is not too concentrated

00:44:19.770 --> 00:44:21.690 align:middle line:90%
inside any segment.

00:44:21.690 --> 00:44:24.570 align:middle line:84%
But even assuming
that we do that,

00:44:24.570 --> 00:44:26.290 align:middle line:84%
we see that we have
lots of problems

00:44:26.290 --> 00:44:29.010 align:middle line:84%
if we try to do
something like this.

00:44:29.010 --> 00:44:30.190 align:middle line:90%
What are the problems?

00:44:30.190 --> 00:44:31.970 align:middle line:84%
So can you tell
me some problems?

00:44:31.970 --> 00:44:36.010 align:middle line:84%
So some challenges in trying
to do something like this.

00:44:36.010 --> 00:44:40.420 align:middle line:84%
If now A is a subset of
let's say 0, 1 or 1, 2--

00:44:40.420 --> 00:44:41.280 align:middle line:90%
let's say 0, 1.

00:44:41.280 --> 00:44:43.260 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't matter.

00:44:43.260 --> 00:44:46.620 align:middle line:84%
So what things you
should be worried about?

00:44:46.620 --> 00:44:47.527 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:44:47.527 --> 00:44:48.860 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: X should be unbounded.

00:44:48.860 --> 00:44:50.960 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: X
could be unbounded.

00:44:50.960 --> 00:44:53.420 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:44:53.420 --> 00:44:57.900 align:middle line:84%
So in the finite field, we need
to avoid 0 in the denominator.

00:44:57.900 --> 00:45:00.600 align:middle line:84%
But in the Euclidean case, we
don't only need to assume 0.

00:45:00.600 --> 00:45:03.380 align:middle line:84%
We should be very worried
about small denominators, not 0

00:45:03.380 --> 00:45:07.420 align:middle line:84%
but small denominators, because
this is going to blow up.

00:45:07.420 --> 00:45:10.500 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, this is
certainly an issue.

00:45:10.500 --> 00:45:12.610 align:middle line:84%
Are there any other issues
one should worry about?

00:45:12.610 --> 00:45:18.380 align:middle line:90%


00:45:18.380 --> 00:45:23.032 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What does it mean
to equal Fp in this case?

00:45:23.032 --> 00:45:24.240 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: That's right.

00:45:24.240 --> 00:45:28.140 align:middle line:84%
Well, I mean, what does
it mean to recall Fp?

00:45:28.140 --> 00:45:29.580 align:middle line:90%
It's not clear.

00:45:29.580 --> 00:45:31.860 align:middle line:84%
I would say what is
even much less clear

00:45:31.860 --> 00:45:33.520 align:middle line:90%
is, What does it mean to add 1?

00:45:33.520 --> 00:45:36.510 align:middle line:90%


00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:41.010 align:middle line:84%
Because I don't know,
R is certainly not--

00:45:41.010 --> 00:45:44.430 align:middle line:84%
I mean, R is invariant
than adding 1.

00:45:44.430 --> 00:45:46.910 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this doesn't
live in 0, 1 anymore.

00:45:46.910 --> 00:45:49.878 align:middle line:84%
If we force it to live in 0,
1 by intersecting with 0, 1,

00:45:49.878 --> 00:45:51.170 align:middle line:90%
there could still be something.

00:45:51.170 --> 00:45:53.250 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if we add 1, we
could still land here.

00:45:53.250 --> 00:45:56.767 align:middle line:84%
So adding 1 doesn't
seem like a good idea.

00:45:56.767 --> 00:45:58.350 align:middle line:84%
From a conceptual
point of view, there

00:45:58.350 --> 00:46:02.130 align:middle line:84%
is something that is even
more worrying, which is here,

00:46:02.130 --> 00:46:06.612 align:middle line:84%
it is crucial that Fp doesn't
have any additive subgroup.

00:46:06.612 --> 00:46:07.570 align:middle line:90%
So it's a simple group.

00:46:07.570 --> 00:46:09.750 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't have any
non-trivial subgroups.

00:46:09.750 --> 00:46:12.610 align:middle line:84%
Because if it had a subgroup,
this wouldn't be true.

00:46:12.610 --> 00:46:15.750 align:middle line:90%


00:46:15.750 --> 00:46:23.630 align:middle line:84%
Now does R have any subfields
or subgroups or subrings?

00:46:23.630 --> 00:46:28.590 align:middle line:84%
Well, first of all, it does have
subgroups, additive subgroups.

00:46:28.590 --> 00:46:32.530 align:middle line:90%
It does of any dimension.

00:46:32.530 --> 00:46:33.910 align:middle line:90%
So, of course, it does.

00:46:33.910 --> 00:46:36.390 align:middle line:84%
All of our rational
numbers, number fields.

00:46:36.390 --> 00:46:38.390 align:middle line:90%
But number fields are countable.

00:46:38.390 --> 00:46:40.770 align:middle line:84%
So we are interested
in larger things.

00:46:40.770 --> 00:46:44.530 align:middle line:84%
But it does have some
groups of intermediate size.

00:46:44.530 --> 00:46:48.290 align:middle line:84%
It does not have subrings
of intermediate size.

00:46:48.290 --> 00:46:50.050 align:middle line:90%
But this is a difficult theorem.

00:46:50.050 --> 00:46:52.510 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it's a consequence
of projection theorem.

00:46:52.510 --> 00:46:54.170 align:middle line:90%
So we cannot really use it.

00:46:54.170 --> 00:46:58.090 align:middle line:84%
So here, we are escaping
because X is not a subring.

00:46:58.090 --> 00:47:04.970 align:middle line:84%
But it's not so clear if there
is a subring type structure here

00:47:04.970 --> 00:47:06.390 align:middle line:90%
in R.

00:47:06.390 --> 00:47:08.670 align:middle line:84%
All of these things
should make it very scary,

00:47:08.670 --> 00:47:12.970 align:middle line:84%
and a normal person would
give up at this stage.

00:47:12.970 --> 00:47:18.310 align:middle line:84%
But there is a paper by
Larry Guth and Josh Zahl,

00:47:18.310 --> 00:47:20.690 align:middle line:84%
my colleague at
UBC, and Etzkowitz,

00:47:20.690 --> 00:47:23.610 align:middle line:84%
where they managed to extend
this idea to the Euclidean

00:47:23.610 --> 00:47:26.310 align:middle line:84%
setting, not to prove
Bourgain's projection theorem--

00:47:26.310 --> 00:47:29.410 align:middle line:84%
to prove some different
related theorem.

00:47:29.410 --> 00:47:36.540 align:middle line:84%
So let me tell you what they
did to overcome these obstacles.

00:47:36.540 --> 00:47:38.893 align:middle line:84%
But first of all, I
should define something

00:47:38.893 --> 00:47:40.310 align:middle line:84%
that I should have
defined before.

00:47:40.310 --> 00:47:42.980 align:middle line:90%


00:47:42.980 --> 00:47:45.545 align:middle line:84%
So we have these
non-concentration conditions.

00:47:45.545 --> 00:47:47.420 align:middle line:84%
So we call these
non-concentration conditions

00:47:47.420 --> 00:47:50.820 align:middle line:84%
because it tells us that X and
D are not concentrated in both,

00:47:50.820 --> 00:47:52.660 align:middle line:90%
non-concentration conditions.

00:47:52.660 --> 00:47:59.460 align:middle line:84%
So looking at this, we are going
to write a definition, which

00:47:59.460 --> 00:48:01.900 align:middle line:84%
is inspired by this
so that we don't

00:48:01.900 --> 00:48:06.080 align:middle line:84%
have to repeat these sorts
of conditions every time.

00:48:06.080 --> 00:48:23.180 align:middle line:90%


00:48:23.180 --> 00:48:25.100 align:middle line:84%
By the way, even
in the finite field

00:48:25.100 --> 00:48:29.590 align:middle line:84%
setting, what Bourgain, Katz,
and Tao did was also not this.

00:48:29.590 --> 00:48:33.590 align:middle line:90%
So this idea came later.

00:48:33.590 --> 00:48:38.830 align:middle line:84%
It originated from Gaurav, which
is after Bourgain, Katz, and Tao

00:48:38.830 --> 00:48:40.650 align:middle line:90%
proved something like this.

00:48:40.650 --> 00:48:43.710 align:middle line:84%
So Bourgain this is something
much, much more complicated.

00:48:43.710 --> 00:48:45.430 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:45.430 --> 00:48:46.330 align:middle line:90%
Definition.

00:48:46.330 --> 00:48:50.190 align:middle line:90%


00:48:50.190 --> 00:48:53.150 align:middle line:84%
A subset of the
unit ball in Rd--

00:48:53.150 --> 00:48:55.910 align:middle line:90%


00:48:55.910 --> 00:48:57.810 align:middle line:84%
we just want to fix
some region of space,

00:48:57.810 --> 00:48:59.310 align:middle line:90%
so why not fix the unit ball?

00:48:59.310 --> 00:49:02.870 align:middle line:90%


00:49:02.870 --> 00:49:07.750 align:middle line:84%
Let delta be between
0 and 1, not 0.

00:49:07.750 --> 00:49:10.150 align:middle line:90%
And maybe also not 1.

00:49:10.150 --> 00:49:13.290 align:middle line:90%
So we say that this is a delta.

00:49:13.290 --> 00:49:17.350 align:middle line:84%
And then we have a parameter
t, which is between 0 and d.

00:49:17.350 --> 00:49:21.190 align:middle line:84%
And then we have a
constant, which is positive,

00:49:21.190 --> 00:49:23.310 align:middle line:90%
let's say at least 1.

00:49:23.310 --> 00:49:28.280 align:middle line:84%
We say that X is
a delta S, C, d.

00:49:28.280 --> 00:49:30.360 align:middle line:84%
So this d tells us
the ambient dimension,

00:49:30.360 --> 00:49:32.300 align:middle line:84%
and I will probably
forget to write it down,

00:49:32.300 --> 00:49:34.600 align:middle line:84%
or it will be
clear from context.

00:49:34.600 --> 00:49:40.040 align:middle line:90%
Set if the following holds.

00:49:40.040 --> 00:49:41.880 align:middle line:90%
If we intersect X--

00:49:41.880 --> 00:49:44.540 align:middle line:84%
so I'm not assuming X
is a union of vaults.

00:49:44.540 --> 00:49:46.300 align:middle line:84%
I'm not assuming X
is delta-separated.

00:49:46.300 --> 00:49:48.680 align:middle line:84%
I'm not assuming anything,
and I'm not assuming anything

00:49:48.680 --> 00:49:51.800 align:middle line:84%
because I'm using to use the
delta-covering number to measure

00:49:51.800 --> 00:49:52.420 align:middle line:90%
things.

00:49:52.420 --> 00:49:55.105 align:middle line:84%
So this is nothing about
the delta-covering number.

00:49:55.105 --> 00:49:56.480 align:middle line:84%
You don't need to
assume anything

00:49:56.480 --> 00:50:00.106 align:middle line:84%
as long as you remember
to write the bad delta.

00:50:00.106 --> 00:50:05.560 align:middle line:84%
So if I intersect
X with the ball

00:50:05.560 --> 00:50:08.280 align:middle line:84%
and measure it by the
delta-covering number,

00:50:08.280 --> 00:50:13.120 align:middle line:84%
this is at most C. So C is the
tolerance, the leeway that I

00:50:13.120 --> 00:50:17.200 align:middle line:90%
have, times R to the s.

00:50:17.200 --> 00:50:20.400 align:middle line:84%
So s measures the
degree of concentration

00:50:20.400 --> 00:50:23.180 align:middle line:84%
of non-concentration, the
degree of non-concentration.

00:50:23.180 --> 00:50:24.600 align:middle line:90%
So the larger the s--

00:50:24.600 --> 00:50:28.170 align:middle line:84%
so R is going to be between 0
and 1, or between delta and one.

00:50:28.170 --> 00:50:29.970 align:middle line:84%
So the larger s,
the smaller this is,

00:50:29.970 --> 00:50:36.610 align:middle line:84%
and the stronger this condition
becomes times the size of X.

00:50:36.610 --> 00:50:40.570 align:middle line:84%
So again, this says that a ball
cannot contain too much of X.

00:50:40.570 --> 00:50:47.330 align:middle line:84%
And this is for every center and
for every radius between delta

00:50:47.330 --> 00:50:49.330 align:middle line:90%
and 1.

00:50:49.330 --> 00:50:50.170 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:50:50.170 --> 00:50:51.690 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The s
is supposed to be

00:50:51.690 --> 00:50:53.390 align:middle line:90%
t unless you use both s and t.

00:50:53.390 --> 00:50:56.450 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Sorry, yes.

00:50:56.450 --> 00:50:58.830 align:middle line:84%
But it could be s or t,
but one has to fix one.

00:50:58.830 --> 00:50:59.690 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, s.

00:50:59.690 --> 00:51:00.390 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:51:00.390 --> 00:51:04.132 align:middle line:90%


00:51:04.132 --> 00:51:06.590 align:middle line:84%
OK, so I hope you agree that
in the statement of Bourgain's

00:51:06.590 --> 00:51:11.090 align:middle line:84%
projection theorem, this is the
condition we have on x and on d.

00:51:11.090 --> 00:51:16.930 align:middle line:84%
On X, we have a t, and
on d, we have an s.

00:51:16.930 --> 00:51:19.030 align:middle line:84%
But this is the
condition that we had.

00:51:19.030 --> 00:51:22.090 align:middle line:84%
And so we can bring them both
under the same umbrella using

00:51:22.090 --> 00:51:23.200 align:middle line:90%
the delta-covering number.

00:51:23.200 --> 00:51:27.310 align:middle line:90%


00:51:27.310 --> 00:51:28.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:28.190 --> 00:51:33.350 align:middle line:84%
This is saying X is not too
concentrated inside small balls.

00:51:33.350 --> 00:51:35.950 align:middle line:84%
And the strength of
concentration is given by s,

00:51:35.950 --> 00:51:40.850 align:middle line:84%
and there is a tolerance given
by C. C could depend on delta.

00:51:40.850 --> 00:51:41.630 align:middle line:90%
So C is anything.

00:51:41.630 --> 00:51:43.470 align:middle line:84%
In particular, it
could depend on delta.

00:51:43.470 --> 00:51:46.070 align:middle line:84%
And in the statement of
Bourgain projection theorem--

00:51:46.070 --> 00:51:48.350 align:middle line:84%
so in Bourgain projection
theorem, this, in fact,

00:51:48.350 --> 00:51:51.270 align:middle line:84%
is going to be delta
to the minus eta.

00:51:51.270 --> 00:51:54.870 align:middle line:84%
So we have a leeway that
increases as a power with delta,

00:51:54.870 --> 00:51:59.042 align:middle line:84%
is very small power but
nevertheless a power.

00:51:59.042 --> 00:52:02.830 align:middle line:90%
So now we can state something.

00:52:02.830 --> 00:52:03.610 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:52:03.610 --> 00:52:10.070 align:middle line:90%


00:52:10.070 --> 00:52:11.510 align:middle line:90%
Lemma.

00:52:11.510 --> 00:52:14.910 align:middle line:84%
So it is the analog of the
first step in the proof.

00:52:14.910 --> 00:52:16.530 align:middle line:90%
So it's the analog of this.

00:52:16.530 --> 00:52:23.280 align:middle line:90%


00:52:23.280 --> 00:52:29.640 align:middle line:84%
Given an s between 0 and
1, there exists an epsilon,

00:52:29.640 --> 00:52:33.320 align:middle line:84%
and all these epsilons
can be taken to depend--

00:52:33.320 --> 00:52:35.880 align:middle line:90%
they depend continuously on s.

00:52:35.880 --> 00:52:37.720 align:middle line:90%
So this is important.

00:52:37.720 --> 00:52:40.440 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:40.440 --> 00:52:43.180 align:middle line:84%
Well, I started saying the
sentence I'm going to finish.

00:52:43.180 --> 00:52:46.248 align:middle line:84%
So in the finite field
setting, one does this.

00:52:46.248 --> 00:52:47.540 align:middle line:90%
And then what is the next step?

00:52:47.540 --> 00:52:50.560 align:middle line:90%
One iterates this.

00:52:50.560 --> 00:52:52.035 align:middle line:90%
And then one keeps growing.

00:52:52.035 --> 00:52:53.660 align:middle line:84%
In order to know that
you keep growing,

00:52:53.660 --> 00:52:56.880 align:middle line:84%
you need to know that this
epsilon remains bounded away

00:52:56.880 --> 00:53:01.360 align:middle line:84%
from 0 as long as the exponent
remains bounded away from 1.

00:53:01.360 --> 00:53:03.820 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the same is
going to be true here,

00:53:03.820 --> 00:53:06.200 align:middle line:84%
although as we will
see next time--

00:53:06.200 --> 00:53:12.040 align:middle line:84%
I think next time is much, much
more complicated to iterate

00:53:12.040 --> 00:53:12.940 align:middle line:90%
in this case.

00:53:12.940 --> 00:53:16.240 align:middle line:84%
But let's focus
on this for today.

00:53:16.240 --> 00:53:22.450 align:middle line:84%
Given s, there is an epsilon
such that the following holds.

00:53:22.450 --> 00:53:29.090 align:middle line:90%
Suppose A is in 0, 1.

00:53:29.090 --> 00:53:34.130 align:middle line:84%
The delta-covering number
is delta to the minus s,

00:53:34.130 --> 00:53:46.020 align:middle line:84%
and A is a delta s is delta to
the epsilon minus epsilon set.

00:53:46.020 --> 00:53:49.890 align:middle line:90%


00:53:49.890 --> 00:53:54.970 align:middle line:84%
So it's very non-concentrated
because s matches the size.

00:53:54.970 --> 00:53:57.210 align:middle line:84%
But on the other hand, there
is quite a bit of leeway

00:53:57.210 --> 00:53:58.740 align:middle line:84%
in this delta to
the minus epsilon.

00:53:58.740 --> 00:54:02.690 align:middle line:90%


00:54:02.690 --> 00:54:10.610 align:middle line:84%
OK, so there exists a polynomial
Q. It could be the same Q,

00:54:10.610 --> 00:54:11.920 align:middle line:90%
so that Q if you want.

00:54:11.920 --> 00:54:15.010 align:middle line:90%


00:54:15.010 --> 00:54:15.725 align:middle line:90%
Any polynomial.

00:54:15.725 --> 00:54:17.850 align:middle line:84%
So really, it doesn't matter
because you can always

00:54:17.850 --> 00:54:18.700 align:middle line:90%
apply Plunnecke-Ruzsa.

00:54:18.700 --> 00:54:19.950 align:middle line:90%
But let's say that polynomial.

00:54:19.950 --> 00:54:22.300 align:middle line:90%
But any polynomial will do.

00:54:22.300 --> 00:54:28.080 align:middle line:90%
Then we have growth.

00:54:28.080 --> 00:54:30.900 align:middle line:84%
I'm just putting delta-covering
number everywhere.

00:54:30.900 --> 00:54:33.420 align:middle line:90%
And we get growth.

00:54:33.420 --> 00:54:38.500 align:middle line:84%
So we get delta minus s,
which was the size of A.

00:54:38.500 --> 00:54:42.970 align:middle line:84%
But we get a delta to the
minus epsilon grow over delta.

00:54:42.970 --> 00:54:54.300 align:middle line:90%


00:54:54.300 --> 00:54:57.580 align:middle line:84%
It looks very, very
similar to that.

00:54:57.580 --> 00:54:58.440 align:middle line:90%
To what?

00:54:58.440 --> 00:55:00.300 align:middle line:90%
To this.

00:55:00.300 --> 00:55:05.340 align:middle line:84%
Except that we need to add this
non-concentration assumption.

00:55:05.340 --> 00:55:07.920 align:middle line:84%
We certainly need to add
something because otherwise,

00:55:07.920 --> 00:55:10.500 align:middle line:84%
if A is just an
interval it's not true,

00:55:10.500 --> 00:55:14.060 align:middle line:84%
it's not clear between
interval and this what happens.

00:55:14.060 --> 00:55:19.470 align:middle line:84%
But OK, with this
assumption, it is true.

00:55:19.470 --> 00:55:22.070 align:middle line:90%
OK, so how can one prove that?

00:55:22.070 --> 00:55:24.190 align:middle line:84%
So we want to use this
strategy, but we saw

00:55:24.190 --> 00:55:25.650 align:middle line:90%
that there are many problems.

00:55:25.650 --> 00:55:27.370 align:middle line:84%
So I'm not going to
do the whole proof.

00:55:27.370 --> 00:55:35.252 align:middle line:84%
But I'm going to tell you how
to solve two of the problems.

00:55:35.252 --> 00:55:36.710 align:middle line:84%
To some degree, I
will tell you how

00:55:36.710 --> 00:55:37.918 align:middle line:90%
to solve two of the problems.

00:55:37.918 --> 00:55:44.750 align:middle line:90%


00:55:44.750 --> 00:55:46.495 align:middle line:90%
One is really cheating, but OK.

00:55:46.495 --> 00:55:47.870 align:middle line:84%
So I guess what
I'm going to tell

00:55:47.870 --> 00:55:50.528 align:middle line:84%
you is that cheating
doesn't always work,

00:55:50.528 --> 00:55:52.820 align:middle line:84%
but it does work in this
case, in this particular case.

00:55:52.820 --> 00:56:12.670 align:middle line:90%


00:56:12.670 --> 00:56:14.170 align:middle line:90%
I should finish at 2:25.

00:56:14.170 --> 00:56:15.960 align:middle line:90%
Is that right?

00:56:15.960 --> 00:56:17.420 align:middle line:90%
OK, plenty of time.

00:56:17.420 --> 00:56:20.240 align:middle line:90%


00:56:20.240 --> 00:56:21.220 align:middle line:90%
The idea of proof.

00:56:21.220 --> 00:56:22.580 align:middle line:90%
I'm not going to prove it, but--

00:56:22.580 --> 00:56:33.760 align:middle line:90%


00:56:33.760 --> 00:56:35.900 align:middle line:84%
in the finite field
setting, this works.

00:56:35.900 --> 00:56:38.560 align:middle line:84%
Here, we have the problem
that the denominator can

00:56:38.560 --> 00:56:41.480 align:middle line:84%
be very small, and then
this could be huge.

00:56:41.480 --> 00:56:46.200 align:middle line:84%
So well, we are going to do
two things at twice to try

00:56:46.200 --> 00:56:49.120 align:middle line:90%
to at least reduce the issue.

00:56:49.120 --> 00:56:51.220 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to define
B in the following way.

00:56:51.220 --> 00:56:54.120 align:middle line:90%


00:56:54.120 --> 00:57:00.260 align:middle line:84%
It is essentially A
minus A over A minus A.

00:57:00.260 --> 00:57:03.120 align:middle line:90%
So we pick some gamma.

00:57:03.120 --> 00:57:05.880 align:middle line:84%
And the gamma in the proof
has to be picked carefully

00:57:05.880 --> 00:57:07.760 align:middle line:90%
so that things work out.

00:57:07.760 --> 00:57:10.240 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to go into
the proof, but you

00:57:10.240 --> 00:57:13.700 align:middle line:84%
would have to pretend that there
is a gamma so that will work.

00:57:13.700 --> 00:57:17.780 align:middle line:84%
OK, so first of all, I
restrict the denominators

00:57:17.780 --> 00:57:19.850 align:middle line:84%
to being larger than
delta to the gamma.

00:57:19.850 --> 00:57:22.500 align:middle line:90%


00:57:22.500 --> 00:57:27.860 align:middle line:84%
In this way, well, I got rid
of the worst possible case

00:57:27.860 --> 00:57:29.980 align:middle line:90%
where the expansion is too much.

00:57:29.980 --> 00:57:33.020 align:middle line:84%
But even then, this could
escape the interval 0, 1.

00:57:33.020 --> 00:57:35.120 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to escape
the interval 0, 1.

00:57:35.120 --> 00:57:38.060 align:middle line:90%


00:57:38.060 --> 00:57:40.320 align:middle line:84%
So I intersect it with
the interval 0, 1.

00:57:40.320 --> 00:57:43.260 align:middle line:90%


00:57:43.260 --> 00:57:50.780 align:middle line:84%
So this B is going to play the
role of X. By doing this, again,

00:57:50.780 --> 00:57:54.280 align:middle line:84%
I'm avoiding two related but
not exactly the same issues.

00:57:54.280 --> 00:57:57.340 align:middle line:84%
One is that this could escape
our reference interval.

00:57:57.340 --> 00:57:59.980 align:middle line:84%
And the other is that the
denominators could be too small.

00:57:59.980 --> 00:58:02.700 align:middle line:84%
They can still be
quite small because--

00:58:02.700 --> 00:58:06.535 align:middle line:84%
so gamma is not zero, so
this can still be small.

00:58:06.535 --> 00:58:09.292 align:middle line:90%
So there is a trade-off.

00:58:09.292 --> 00:58:11.250 align:middle line:84%
If we allow two small
denominators denominator,

00:58:11.250 --> 00:58:12.510 align:middle line:90%
things blow up too much.

00:58:12.510 --> 00:58:14.490 align:middle line:84%
But we still have to
allow small denominators.

00:58:14.490 --> 00:58:16.070 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, we are
missing too much

00:58:16.070 --> 00:58:20.090 align:middle line:84%
of A minus A over A
minus A. So this gamma

00:58:20.090 --> 00:58:23.350 align:middle line:90%
gives us the trade off.

00:58:23.350 --> 00:58:26.110 align:middle line:90%
So that's one thing we do.

00:58:26.110 --> 00:58:28.550 align:middle line:84%
But the most important
thing to understand

00:58:28.550 --> 00:58:31.650 align:middle line:84%
is, What do we do
instead of this?

00:58:31.650 --> 00:58:33.085 align:middle line:84%
So really, adding
1 doesn't really

00:58:33.085 --> 00:58:34.210 align:middle line:90%
make sense in this setting.

00:58:34.210 --> 00:58:36.350 align:middle line:90%
So what do we do?

00:58:36.350 --> 00:58:41.190 align:middle line:84%
Here comes a very easy but
absolutely critical lemma.

00:58:41.190 --> 00:58:45.350 align:middle line:84%
So in the same way
that the method in Fp

00:58:45.350 --> 00:58:50.170 align:middle line:84%
doesn't work in Fp
squared, what works in R--

00:58:50.170 --> 00:58:52.010 align:middle line:84%
this is a remark I
should have made earlier,

00:58:52.010 --> 00:58:55.490 align:middle line:84%
but I don't think we have
the statement anymore.

00:58:55.490 --> 00:58:57.990 align:middle line:84%
We don't have the statement of
Bourgain's projection theorem

00:58:57.990 --> 00:58:58.490 align:middle line:90%
anymore.

00:58:58.490 --> 00:59:00.310 align:middle line:84%
But Bourgain projection
theorem is not

00:59:00.310 --> 00:59:04.230 align:middle line:84%
true Over C, because
over C, you could

00:59:04.230 --> 00:59:09.480 align:middle line:84%
take X to be essentially R
squared, leaving in C squared.

00:59:09.480 --> 00:59:12.440 align:middle line:84%
You could take D to be
a piece of R, leaving

00:59:12.440 --> 00:59:16.500 align:middle line:84%
in C. Because R is a subring
of C, you don't escape.

00:59:16.500 --> 00:59:18.240 align:middle line:90%
So there is no growth.

00:59:18.240 --> 00:59:20.040 align:middle line:84%
So it's exactly
the same reason why

00:59:20.040 --> 00:59:21.440 align:middle line:90%
it doesn't work in Fp squared.

00:59:21.440 --> 00:59:24.360 align:middle line:84%
Because Fp squared has
an intermediate algebraic

00:59:24.360 --> 00:59:25.220 align:middle line:90%
structure.

00:59:25.220 --> 00:59:27.800 align:middle line:84%
C has an intermediate
algebraic structure which is R.

00:59:27.800 --> 00:59:30.520 align:middle line:84%
And because of this,
it doesn't work.

00:59:30.520 --> 00:59:34.160 align:middle line:84%
And here, we use
that Fp doesn't have

00:59:34.160 --> 00:59:35.960 align:middle line:84%
an intermediate
algebraic structure.

00:59:35.960 --> 00:59:39.160 align:middle line:84%
So actually, this lemma is
very crucial in the sense

00:59:39.160 --> 00:59:46.180 align:middle line:84%
that it is what distinguishes R
from C or for many other things,

00:59:46.180 --> 00:59:52.360 align:middle line:84%
but in particular,
from C. So there

00:59:52.360 --> 00:59:55.000 align:middle line:84%
are many ways in which
R is different from C.

00:59:55.000 --> 01:00:01.080 align:middle line:84%
We will see that it is the order
structure, what distinguishes R

01:00:01.080 --> 01:00:03.182 align:middle line:84%
from C in the lemma, in
the proof of the lemma.

01:00:03.182 --> 01:00:05.140 align:middle line:84%
Actually, the lemma can
be proved in many ways,

01:00:05.140 --> 01:00:07.140 align:middle line:84%
and some of them do not
use the order structure.

01:00:07.140 --> 01:00:09.310 align:middle line:84%
But in my proof, I will
use the order structure.

01:00:09.310 --> 01:00:11.610 align:middle line:90%
OK, so here is the lemma.

01:00:11.610 --> 01:00:15.870 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that B. Eventually, we
are going to apply to this B.

01:00:15.870 --> 01:00:18.890 align:middle line:84%
That's why I call it B.
But a priori is any B,

01:00:18.890 --> 01:00:21.050 align:middle line:90%
is contained in 0, 1.

01:00:21.050 --> 01:00:24.650 align:middle line:84%
And suppose that 0 is
in B. 0 is in this B

01:00:24.650 --> 01:00:28.630 align:middle line:90%
because a1 could be equal to a2.

01:00:28.630 --> 01:00:43.550 align:middle line:84%
And then let rho be
the largest gap in B.

01:00:43.550 --> 01:00:45.090 align:middle line:90%
What is the largest gap?

01:00:45.090 --> 01:00:50.210 align:middle line:84%
So a gap is a connected
component of the complement.

01:00:50.210 --> 01:00:54.330 align:middle line:84%
So we are in R. So connected
components are segments.

01:00:54.330 --> 01:00:56.688 align:middle line:84%
So the complement is
a union of segments.

01:00:56.688 --> 01:00:57.730 align:middle line:90%
Well, it could be points.

01:00:57.730 --> 01:00:58.990 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it could be dense.

01:00:58.990 --> 01:01:00.570 align:middle line:90%
But let's imagine B is closed.

01:01:00.570 --> 01:01:02.330 align:middle line:84%
I think it doesn't
have to be closed.

01:01:02.330 --> 01:01:04.290 align:middle line:90%
Maybe let's say closed.

01:01:04.290 --> 01:01:07.100 align:middle line:90%
It's not really important.

01:01:07.100 --> 01:01:09.020 align:middle line:84%
If it's closed
and the complement

01:01:09.020 --> 01:01:13.420 align:middle line:84%
is a finite or countable
union of open intervals.

01:01:13.420 --> 01:01:16.170 align:middle line:84%
Each of them has a length,
and we take the supremum.

01:01:16.170 --> 01:01:19.460 align:middle line:90%


01:01:19.460 --> 01:01:23.680 align:middle line:84%
Everything is going to be
finitary in our application.

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:26.420 align:middle line:84%
But let's say the largest
in the sense of the supremum

01:01:26.420 --> 01:01:28.633 align:middle line:90%
of the length of the gaps in B.

01:01:28.633 --> 01:01:29.800 align:middle line:90%
So is it clear what this is?

01:01:29.800 --> 01:01:31.633 align:middle line:84%
We just look at the
complementary intervals,

01:01:31.633 --> 01:01:33.660 align:middle line:90%
and we look at the largest one.

01:01:33.660 --> 01:01:47.273 align:middle line:84%
Then there exists B in B such
that either the distance from B

01:01:47.273 --> 01:01:55.860 align:middle line:84%
over 2 to B is at least rho
over 4 or the distance from B

01:01:55.860 --> 01:02:02.400 align:middle line:84%
plus 1 over 2 to B is
at least rho over 4.

01:02:02.400 --> 01:02:13.730 align:middle line:90%


01:02:13.730 --> 01:02:15.960 align:middle line:90%
So proof.

01:02:15.960 --> 01:02:21.360 align:middle line:84%
Let B prime be B over 2
union B plus 1 over 2.

01:02:21.360 --> 01:02:23.420 align:middle line:84%
This means what you
expect it to mean.

01:02:23.420 --> 01:02:26.600 align:middle line:84%
So you take little b
and B divide it by 2.

01:02:26.600 --> 01:02:28.340 align:middle line:84%
And you do that for
every little b and B.

01:02:28.340 --> 01:02:31.200 align:middle line:84%
And then you take
little b plus 1 over 2

01:02:31.200 --> 01:02:36.200 align:middle line:84%
for every little b and B. So I
hope it's clear what this is.

01:02:36.200 --> 01:02:40.220 align:middle line:84%
This is containing 0, 1 as well,
because B is containing 0, 1.

01:02:40.220 --> 01:02:42.320 align:middle line:90%
So this is contained in 0, 1/2.

01:02:42.320 --> 01:02:43.940 align:middle line:90%
This is containing 1/2, 1.

01:02:43.940 --> 01:02:46.480 align:middle line:90%


01:02:46.480 --> 01:02:47.120 align:middle line:90%
So we have 0.

01:02:47.120 --> 01:02:47.620 align:middle line:90%
We have 1.

01:02:47.620 --> 01:02:48.600 align:middle line:90%
We have 1/2.

01:02:48.600 --> 01:03:00.640 align:middle line:84%
And 1/2 is in B prime
because 0 is in B.

01:03:00.640 --> 01:03:02.220 align:middle line:84%
You will see that
this is important.

01:03:02.220 --> 01:03:05.330 align:middle line:84%
So 0 is in B. So
1/2 is in B prime.

01:03:05.330 --> 01:03:07.080 align:middle line:84%
Now what is the
largest gap in B prime?

01:03:07.080 --> 01:03:09.730 align:middle line:90%


01:03:09.730 --> 01:03:12.070 align:middle line:84%
So by definition, the
largest gap in B is rho.

01:03:12.070 --> 01:03:13.570 align:middle line:90%
So that's the definition of rho.

01:03:13.570 --> 01:03:16.215 align:middle line:84%
So what is the largest
gap in B prime?

01:03:16.215 --> 01:03:17.090 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Rho over 2.

01:03:17.090 --> 01:03:19.530 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Rho over 2.

01:03:19.530 --> 01:03:21.610 align:middle line:84%
Here, the largest
gap is rho over 2

01:03:21.610 --> 01:03:23.770 align:middle line:84%
because I'm scaling
down by a factor of 2.

01:03:23.770 --> 01:03:25.530 align:middle line:84%
And here, the largest
gap is rho over 2

01:03:25.530 --> 01:03:27.890 align:middle line:84%
because I'm translating
a scaling down by--

01:03:27.890 --> 01:03:28.690 align:middle line:90%
yes.

01:03:28.690 --> 01:03:31.148 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So we know actually
there'll be a gap of size rho

01:03:31.148 --> 01:03:35.730 align:middle line:84%
if B has a big gap at the
ends of the intervals?

01:03:35.730 --> 01:03:40.770 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: So
I guess maybe let's

01:03:40.770 --> 01:03:43.730 align:middle line:84%
assume that 1 is also in
B or something like this.

01:03:43.730 --> 01:03:46.290 align:middle line:84%
So I mean, there could
be an infinite gap.

01:03:46.290 --> 01:03:48.970 align:middle line:84%
Is that what you're
worried about?

01:03:48.970 --> 01:03:52.210 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
there's a gap from 1

01:03:52.210 --> 01:03:57.068 align:middle line:84%
minus rho to 1 or something,
but if 1 is in B then.

01:03:57.068 --> 01:03:59.110 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Well,
let's say 0 and 1 are in B.

01:03:59.110 --> 01:04:00.980 align:middle line:84%
So 1 is also here
because you could

01:04:00.980 --> 01:04:04.340 align:middle line:90%
take a3 and a4 to be a1 and a2.

01:04:04.340 --> 01:04:08.940 align:middle line:84%
So 1 is in B. If you define
the gap in a way that

01:04:08.940 --> 01:04:11.040 align:middle line:84%
avoids this issue, you
don't need 1 to be in B,

01:04:11.040 --> 01:04:13.858 align:middle line:90%
but it's not important.

01:04:13.858 --> 01:04:15.400 align:middle line:84%
Why is it important
that 1/2 is in B?

01:04:15.400 --> 01:04:18.720 align:middle line:84%
Because here, the largest
gap has size rho over 2.

01:04:18.720 --> 01:04:20.660 align:middle line:84%
Here, the largest gap
has size rho over 2.

01:04:20.660 --> 01:04:25.060 align:middle line:84%
But if 1/2 wasn't here, they
could be combined to form

01:04:25.060 --> 01:04:26.760 align:middle line:90%
a larger gap going across.

01:04:26.760 --> 01:04:30.080 align:middle line:84%
But it cannot go across
because 1/2 is there.

01:04:30.080 --> 01:04:37.460 align:middle line:90%


01:04:37.460 --> 01:04:41.540 align:middle line:84%
Now let's draw the largest
gap or the gap that

01:04:41.540 --> 01:04:43.300 align:middle line:90%
approximates the largest gap.

01:04:43.300 --> 01:04:46.610 align:middle line:84%
So this one has size, let's
say, rho minus epsilon.

01:04:46.610 --> 01:04:50.620 align:middle line:90%


01:04:50.620 --> 01:04:51.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:51.120 --> 01:04:53.140 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
center of the gap.

01:04:53.140 --> 01:04:55.500 align:middle line:84%
So this is the gap
in B, not in B prime.

01:04:55.500 --> 01:05:04.590 align:middle line:84%
In B. Now let's draw an
interval in the middle of length

01:05:04.590 --> 01:05:05.610 align:middle line:90%
rho over 2.

01:05:05.610 --> 01:05:09.270 align:middle line:90%


01:05:09.270 --> 01:05:11.830 align:middle line:90%
Maybe a closed interval.

01:05:11.830 --> 01:05:16.110 align:middle line:84%
This closed interval contains
an element of B prime,

01:05:16.110 --> 01:05:18.910 align:middle line:84%
because the largest gap
of B prime is rho over 2.

01:05:18.910 --> 01:05:21.190 align:middle line:84%
That means that any interval
of length rho over 2

01:05:21.190 --> 01:05:23.190 align:middle line:90%
contains a point in B prime.

01:05:23.190 --> 01:05:24.850 align:middle line:90%
So maybe let's write this down.

01:05:24.850 --> 01:05:37.070 align:middle line:84%
So largest gap--
so this interval

01:05:37.070 --> 01:05:39.750 align:middle line:90%
contains a point in B prime.

01:05:39.750 --> 01:05:42.070 align:middle line:84%
But this point is
at distance at least

01:05:42.070 --> 01:05:47.510 align:middle line:84%
rho over 4 from B because
this gap is double the size.

01:05:47.510 --> 01:05:49.645 align:middle line:84%
So even if the point was
at one of the endpoints--

01:05:49.645 --> 01:05:50.770 align:middle line:90%
so the point could be here.

01:05:50.770 --> 01:05:53.930 align:middle line:84%
But even if it was one of the
endpoints, this is rho over 4.

01:05:53.930 --> 01:05:55.050 align:middle line:90%
This is rho over 4.

01:05:55.050 --> 01:05:59.700 align:middle line:90%


01:05:59.700 --> 01:06:01.540 align:middle line:84%
So maybe let's do
a larger picture.

01:06:01.540 --> 01:06:11.430 align:middle line:84%
So this is rho minus epsilon gap
in B. This is a rho interval.

01:06:11.430 --> 01:06:15.440 align:middle line:90%


01:06:15.440 --> 01:06:21.080 align:middle line:84%
So it contains some
point in B prime.

01:06:21.080 --> 01:06:23.340 align:middle line:84%
Because the largest
gap in B prime is rho.

01:06:23.340 --> 01:06:24.740 align:middle line:84%
And this interval
has length rho.

01:06:24.740 --> 01:06:26.115 align:middle line:84%
So it cannot be
completely empty.

01:06:26.115 --> 01:06:28.660 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, it would
be a larger gap.

01:06:28.660 --> 01:06:30.440 align:middle line:84%
Whichever point is
in this interval

01:06:30.440 --> 01:06:33.760 align:middle line:84%
is at large distance from B
because there is nothing in B

01:06:33.760 --> 01:06:36.120 align:middle line:90%
here.

01:06:36.120 --> 01:06:37.600 align:middle line:90%
So that's the proof.

01:06:37.600 --> 01:06:42.040 align:middle line:84%
So you do the calculation
is at least rho over 4.

01:06:42.040 --> 01:06:45.200 align:middle line:84%
Maybe rho over 5, because
you need to take into account

01:06:45.200 --> 01:06:46.600 align:middle line:90%
this epsilon.

01:06:46.600 --> 01:06:49.720 align:middle line:90%
Maybe rho over 5, just in case.

01:06:49.720 --> 01:06:51.180 align:middle line:90%
It's not important.

01:06:51.180 --> 01:06:54.520 align:middle line:90%


01:06:54.520 --> 01:06:56.990 align:middle line:84%
So you see that this is a
simple geometric argument,

01:06:56.990 --> 01:07:01.050 align:middle line:84%
but it's very, very strongly
uses the order structure of R.

01:07:01.050 --> 01:07:03.970 align:middle line:84%
So this argument doesn't work
in C because there is no order.

01:07:03.970 --> 01:07:06.770 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it cannot work because
what we are going to prove using

01:07:06.770 --> 01:07:11.070 align:middle line:84%
this is not true over C.
Any questions about this?

01:07:11.070 --> 01:07:15.950 align:middle line:90%


01:07:15.950 --> 01:07:17.790 align:middle line:84%
You can prove this
lemma in other ways.

01:07:17.790 --> 01:07:20.930 align:middle line:84%
So both Katz and
Zahl in their paper,

01:07:20.930 --> 01:07:22.390 align:middle line:84%
I think they don't
do this proof,

01:07:22.390 --> 01:07:26.250 align:middle line:84%
but I think this proof is
easier and shows how the order

01:07:26.250 --> 01:07:27.630 align:middle line:90%
structure is fundamental.

01:07:27.630 --> 01:07:32.250 align:middle line:90%


01:07:32.250 --> 01:07:35.290 align:middle line:84%
Hopefully, I have
proved the lemma.

01:07:35.290 --> 01:07:37.380 align:middle line:84%
Of course, a point in B
prime has either this form

01:07:37.380 --> 01:07:39.630 align:middle line:84%
or this form because that's
the definition of B prime.

01:07:39.630 --> 01:07:44.490 align:middle line:84%
So here, we have a B prime in
B prime, which is far from B

01:07:44.490 --> 01:07:46.890 align:middle line:84%
But B prime is
either this or this

01:07:46.890 --> 01:07:49.290 align:middle line:84%
because that's the
definition of B prime.

01:07:49.290 --> 01:07:52.650 align:middle line:84%
So that's how one
concludes the proof.

01:07:52.650 --> 01:07:53.660 align:middle line:90%
Any questions again?

01:07:53.660 --> 01:07:57.110 align:middle line:90%


01:07:57.110 --> 01:08:00.950 align:middle line:90%
OK, so now what?

01:08:00.950 --> 01:08:06.270 align:middle line:84%
The idea is to use B
over 2 or B plus 1 over 2

01:08:06.270 --> 01:08:11.550 align:middle line:90%
instead of B plus 1.

01:08:11.550 --> 01:08:13.950 align:middle line:90%
So why does B plus 1 work?

01:08:13.950 --> 01:08:18.310 align:middle line:84%
So what is important about
B plus 1 or X plus 1?

01:08:18.310 --> 01:08:24.170 align:middle line:84%
So what is important is that,
again, it's a polynomial.

01:08:24.170 --> 01:08:28.790 align:middle line:84%
In this case, it's
a linear polynomial

01:08:28.790 --> 01:08:30.430 align:middle line:84%
that takes something
in X and lands

01:08:30.430 --> 01:08:34.910 align:middle line:84%
it not in X. Well, the
same is true for B over 2

01:08:34.910 --> 01:08:36.250 align:middle line:90%
and B plus 1 over 2.

01:08:36.250 --> 01:08:39.229 align:middle line:90%


01:08:39.229 --> 01:08:51.720 align:middle line:84%
You take something in B,
and it lands far from B.

01:08:51.720 --> 01:08:54.620 align:middle line:84%
It's a first step of proof,
so I'm not going to prove.

01:08:54.620 --> 01:08:58.760 align:middle line:90%


01:08:58.760 --> 01:09:01.660 align:middle line:84%
Well, we have to pick a
rho in 0, 1 carefully.

01:09:01.660 --> 01:09:07.640 align:middle line:90%


01:09:07.640 --> 01:09:09.439 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it's going
to be a power of delta

01:09:09.439 --> 01:09:12.279 align:middle line:90%
as usual, some power.

01:09:12.279 --> 01:09:13.500 align:middle line:90%
Don't remember which power.

01:09:13.500 --> 01:09:15.760 align:middle line:84%
One has to choose
this power carefully.

01:09:15.760 --> 01:09:18.200 align:middle line:84%
And then there
are two cases that

01:09:18.200 --> 01:09:19.869 align:middle line:84%
morally correspond
to those two cases.

01:09:19.869 --> 01:09:26.600 align:middle line:90%


01:09:26.600 --> 01:09:32.240 align:middle line:84%
B now is that B. That B up
there, not an arbitrary.

01:09:32.240 --> 01:09:35.160 align:middle line:90%
That B, is rho dense.

01:09:35.160 --> 01:09:37.680 align:middle line:90%


01:09:37.680 --> 01:09:42.080 align:middle line:84%
Rho dense means that the
largest gap is at most rho.

01:09:42.080 --> 01:09:43.819 align:middle line:84%
Or if you take the
rho neighborhood,

01:09:43.819 --> 01:09:46.020 align:middle line:90%
you cover everything.

01:09:46.020 --> 01:09:48.920 align:middle line:90%
Everything is 0, 1.

01:09:48.920 --> 01:09:52.059 align:middle line:84%
So any questions about
what rho dense means?

01:09:52.059 --> 01:09:55.930 align:middle line:90%


01:09:55.930 --> 01:10:02.690 align:middle line:84%
Here, we use an argument, which
is similar to the case X minus X

01:10:02.690 --> 01:10:09.410 align:middle line:84%
over X. Sorry, it's not
X. It's A minus A over A

01:10:09.410 --> 01:10:18.870 align:middle line:84%
minus A equals Fp to get growth,
which I'm not going to show.

01:10:18.870 --> 01:10:21.410 align:middle line:90%


01:10:21.410 --> 01:10:25.010 align:middle line:90%
This is the easier case.

01:10:25.010 --> 01:10:28.890 align:middle line:84%
I guess here, what's
also the easier case.

01:10:28.890 --> 01:10:33.130 align:middle line:84%
The other possibility is that
there exists a B in B such

01:10:33.130 --> 01:10:48.740 align:middle line:84%
that either B over 2 is far
from B or B plus 1 over 2

01:10:48.740 --> 01:10:55.300 align:middle line:90%
is far from B. In the sense--

01:10:55.300 --> 01:10:59.460 align:middle line:84%
so there are two
cases by the lemma.

01:10:59.460 --> 01:11:02.260 align:middle line:84%
And then we use over
2 or B plus 1 over 2

01:11:02.260 --> 01:11:05.260 align:middle line:84%
in a similar way to
the way that X plus 1

01:11:05.260 --> 01:11:06.870 align:middle line:84%
was used in the
finite field setting.

01:11:06.870 --> 01:11:17.020 align:middle line:90%


01:11:17.020 --> 01:11:20.740 align:middle line:90%
To get expansion.

01:11:20.740 --> 01:11:21.780 align:middle line:90%
It works.

01:11:21.780 --> 01:11:23.240 align:middle line:90%
It's much more complicated.

01:11:23.240 --> 01:11:26.260 align:middle line:84%
So the actual details
are much more complicated

01:11:26.260 --> 01:11:28.210 align:middle line:84%
than in the finite
field setting.

01:11:28.210 --> 01:11:32.180 align:middle line:90%


01:11:32.180 --> 01:11:32.960 align:middle line:90%
But it works.

01:11:32.960 --> 01:11:35.940 align:middle line:90%


01:11:35.940 --> 01:11:40.160 align:middle line:84%
I would say the overall
idea is very similar,

01:11:40.160 --> 01:11:42.040 align:middle line:84%
but the details are
much more complicated.

01:11:42.040 --> 01:11:44.980 align:middle line:90%


01:11:44.980 --> 01:11:45.786 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:45.786 --> 01:11:47.050 align:middle line:90%
So far, so good.

01:11:47.050 --> 01:11:48.790 align:middle line:90%
Modulo, lots of details.

01:11:48.790 --> 01:11:52.710 align:middle line:84%
But this was the first step
in the finite field setting,

01:11:52.710 --> 01:11:55.270 align:middle line:90%
and we can replicate it.

01:11:55.270 --> 01:11:57.910 align:middle line:84%
So it seems that
things are going well.

01:11:57.910 --> 01:11:59.560 align:middle line:84%
But now we have a
much bigger issue.

01:11:59.560 --> 01:12:02.470 align:middle line:90%


01:12:02.470 --> 01:12:04.770 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I'm going to explain
the much bigger issue

01:12:04.770 --> 01:12:09.550 align:middle line:84%
and talk about how to overcome
it next time, because this

01:12:09.550 --> 01:12:12.630 align:middle line:84%
is maybe the biggest issue,
the biggest difference.

01:12:12.630 --> 01:12:14.670 align:middle line:84%
You can see that
this was already

01:12:14.670 --> 01:12:16.810 align:middle line:84%
a big issue and a big
difference in the proof.

01:12:16.810 --> 01:12:20.323 align:middle line:84%
But now comes, I would
say, a bigger issue.

01:12:20.323 --> 01:12:22.490 align:middle line:84%
This was the first step in
the finite field setting.

01:12:22.490 --> 01:12:24.657 align:middle line:84%
What is the second step in
the finite field setting?

01:12:24.657 --> 01:12:26.310 align:middle line:90%
Iterating the first step.

01:12:26.310 --> 01:12:27.410 align:middle line:90%
And you just iterate.

01:12:27.410 --> 01:12:29.490 align:middle line:84%
Nobody is preventing
you from iterating.

01:12:29.490 --> 01:12:31.890 align:middle line:90%
So you get that Q of A growth.

01:12:31.890 --> 01:12:38.490 align:middle line:84%
So you can do Q of Q of A.
So here, maybe let's call it.

01:12:38.490 --> 01:12:41.070 align:middle line:90%
The second step.

01:12:41.070 --> 01:12:48.570 align:middle line:84%
You look at Q of Q of Q of Q
of A. And this is very large.

01:12:48.570 --> 01:12:56.290 align:middle line:84%
So you can make it as close to p
as you want in terms of powers.

01:12:56.290 --> 01:12:59.010 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

01:12:59.010 --> 01:12:59.770 align:middle line:90%
I don't know, eta.

01:12:59.770 --> 01:13:03.690 align:middle line:84%
So for any eta, if we iterate
enough times, we keep growing,

01:13:03.690 --> 01:13:06.390 align:middle line:84%
and we can reach
any power we want.

01:13:06.390 --> 01:13:08.850 align:middle line:84%
In fact, eventually,
in hindsight,

01:13:08.850 --> 01:13:12.070 align:middle line:84%
we get all of the finite
field after iterating

01:13:12.070 --> 01:13:12.950 align:middle line:90%
finitely many times.

01:13:12.950 --> 01:13:14.950 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if you
saw this, but anyway.

01:13:14.950 --> 01:13:18.710 align:middle line:84%
So this is clear because
we just keep iterating.

01:13:18.710 --> 01:13:20.270 align:middle line:90%
So now let's go back to--

01:13:20.270 --> 01:13:27.130 align:middle line:90%


01:13:27.130 --> 01:13:28.500 align:middle line:90%
sorry, did I ever state--

01:13:28.500 --> 01:13:35.930 align:middle line:90%


01:13:35.930 --> 01:13:38.810 align:middle line:90%
oh, here it is.

01:13:38.810 --> 01:13:42.360 align:middle line:84%
Here is the lemma
that I told you

01:13:42.360 --> 01:13:46.140 align:middle line:90%
we can prove using this idea.

01:13:46.140 --> 01:13:47.320 align:middle line:90%
So this is the lemma.

01:13:47.320 --> 01:13:50.660 align:middle line:84%
So we have a delta s delta
to the minus epsilon set

01:13:50.660 --> 01:13:52.180 align:middle line:90%
of size delta to the minus s.

01:13:52.180 --> 01:13:56.220 align:middle line:84%
Then we apply Q,
and the size grows.

01:13:56.220 --> 01:13:58.620 align:middle line:90%
So what's the problem?

01:13:58.620 --> 01:14:02.100 align:middle line:84%
We would like to
iterate, but we cannot.

01:14:02.100 --> 01:14:04.260 align:middle line:90%
So why can we not iterate?

01:14:04.260 --> 01:14:05.400 align:middle line:90%
Well, a priori we cannot.

01:14:05.400 --> 01:14:07.880 align:middle line:84%
I'm not saying-- in the
end, we will iterate.

01:14:07.880 --> 01:14:13.140 align:middle line:84%
But why is it completely
unclear whether we can iterate?

01:14:13.140 --> 01:14:14.900 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: There's no
guarantee that Q of A

01:14:14.900 --> 01:14:16.880 align:middle line:84%
will satisfy the
spacing condition?

01:14:16.880 --> 01:14:18.060 align:middle line:90%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Exactly.

01:14:18.060 --> 01:14:19.220 align:middle line:90%
That's the issue.

01:14:19.220 --> 01:14:21.100 align:middle line:90%
And it is a big issue.

01:14:21.100 --> 01:14:24.380 align:middle line:84%
So we know that the
size of Q of A grows.

01:14:24.380 --> 01:14:26.460 align:middle line:84%
But here, we have this
additional assumption

01:14:26.460 --> 01:14:28.480 align:middle line:84%
and we need it, or we
need some assumption.

01:14:28.480 --> 01:14:31.100 align:middle line:84%
We need the assumption that A
is a delta s delta to the minus

01:14:31.100 --> 01:14:32.260 align:middle line:90%
epsilon set.

01:14:32.260 --> 01:14:34.460 align:middle line:84%
So in order to
iterate, we would need

01:14:34.460 --> 01:14:37.980 align:middle line:84%
to know that not only Q
of A has grown in size,

01:14:37.980 --> 01:14:42.590 align:middle line:84%
but we would need to know that
Q of is A delta, s plus epsilon

01:14:42.590 --> 01:14:44.870 align:middle line:90%
delta to the minus epsilon set.

01:14:44.870 --> 01:14:47.230 align:middle line:90%
And we don't know that a priori.

01:14:47.230 --> 01:14:50.310 align:middle line:84%
If we go over the proof,
the proof doesn't show that.

01:14:50.310 --> 01:14:53.450 align:middle line:84%
So when we-- so I haven't
given the proof of the lemma,

01:14:53.450 --> 01:14:54.990 align:middle line:90%
only gave a very rough sketch.

01:14:54.990 --> 01:14:57.830 align:middle line:84%
But you have to trust me that
if you go through the proof,

01:14:57.830 --> 01:15:00.250 align:middle line:84%
we do not get any
non-concentration for Q of A.

01:15:00.250 --> 01:15:03.160 align:middle line:84%
We literally only get
growth at scale delta.

01:15:03.160 --> 01:15:05.710 align:middle line:90%


01:15:05.710 --> 01:15:07.770 align:middle line:90%
So let me write this somewhere.

01:15:07.770 --> 01:15:23.830 align:middle line:90%


01:15:23.830 --> 01:15:24.540 align:middle line:90%
Big issue.

01:15:24.540 --> 01:15:31.830 align:middle line:90%


01:15:31.830 --> 01:15:44.080 align:middle line:84%
We know Q of A grows in
delta-covering number,

01:15:44.080 --> 01:16:01.960 align:middle line:84%
but the proof does
not show that Q of A

01:16:01.960 --> 01:16:07.188 align:middle line:84%
is delta s plus epsilon
could be a different epsilon.

01:16:07.188 --> 01:16:07.980 align:middle line:90%
That's what we did.

01:16:07.980 --> 01:16:09.730 align:middle line:84%
The same epsilon, but
we need some epsilon

01:16:09.730 --> 01:16:10.910 align:middle line:90%
if we want to iterate here.

01:16:10.910 --> 01:16:35.400 align:middle line:90%


01:16:35.400 --> 01:16:39.330 align:middle line:84%
So we are going to talk about
some of the things we do to

01:16:39.330 --> 01:16:42.010 align:middle line:84%
overcome this in
the next lecture.

01:16:42.010 --> 01:16:46.650 align:middle line:84%
But let me say that I think, in
fact, it is not true that Q of A

01:16:46.650 --> 01:16:51.210 align:middle line:84%
has to be a delta s plus epsilon
delta to the minus epsilon set.

01:16:51.210 --> 01:16:52.430 align:middle line:90%
It is not even true.

01:16:52.430 --> 01:16:57.050 align:middle line:84%
But what is true is that
Q of A contains delta

01:16:57.050 --> 01:16:59.550 align:middle line:84%
s plus epsilon delta to
the minus epsilon set.

01:16:59.550 --> 01:17:37.580 align:middle line:90%


01:17:37.580 --> 01:17:39.580 align:middle line:84%
This is good enough
because we just

01:17:39.580 --> 01:17:42.020 align:middle line:84%
take the subset and
use that to iterate.

01:17:42.020 --> 01:17:44.180 align:middle line:90%
And then we can iterate.

01:17:44.180 --> 01:17:46.540 align:middle line:84%
And the second step will
work in the same way,

01:17:46.540 --> 01:17:49.820 align:middle line:90%
but this is a big issue.

01:17:49.820 --> 01:17:52.420 align:middle line:84%
Somehow, we have to go through
the whole steps of the proof

01:17:52.420 --> 01:17:56.860 align:middle line:84%
in the finite field
setting just to get this.

01:17:56.860 --> 01:17:58.480 align:middle line:84%
And then we have
to do the full--

01:17:58.480 --> 01:18:01.980 align:middle line:84%
so one has to cycle through all
the steps twice in this proof.

01:18:01.980 --> 01:18:05.060 align:middle line:84%
The first cycle is
to solve this issue.

01:18:05.060 --> 01:18:06.820 align:middle line:84%
So we have to use
one of so many hours,

01:18:06.820 --> 01:18:09.410 align:middle line:84%
for example, to
solve this issue.

01:18:09.410 --> 01:18:11.660 align:middle line:84%
That comes much later in the
proof in the finite field

01:18:11.660 --> 01:18:12.040 align:middle line:90%
setting.

01:18:12.040 --> 01:18:13.915 align:middle line:84%
And then we have to use
it again once we have

01:18:13.915 --> 01:18:19.100 align:middle line:90%
expanded a lot by iterating.

01:18:19.100 --> 01:18:23.320 align:middle line:84%
So I'll explain the ideas
behind this on Thursday.

01:18:23.320 --> 01:18:23.900 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:18:23.900 --> 01:18:25.358 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: After
showing that Q of A

01:18:25.358 --> 01:18:27.883 align:middle line:84%
contains a delta X plus
epsilon delta minus epsilon

01:18:27.883 --> 01:18:29.300 align:middle line:84%
set, does that set
have to be kind

01:18:29.300 --> 01:18:33.280 align:middle line:84%
of very close to the size
of A, and unlike like an s

01:18:33.280 --> 01:18:36.180 align:middle line:84%
plus epsilon or
delta spacing level?

01:18:36.180 --> 01:18:39.840 align:middle line:90%


01:18:39.840 --> 01:18:41.813 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: Well,
it needs to be much--

01:18:41.813 --> 01:18:43.980 align:middle line:84%
something maybe I should
have said, but I didn't say

01:18:43.980 --> 01:18:47.320 align:middle line:90%
is that a delta TC--

01:18:47.320 --> 01:18:48.460 align:middle line:90%
ignore this for a moment.

01:18:48.460 --> 01:18:54.080 align:middle line:84%
So delta TC set has size at
least delta to the minus t.

01:18:54.080 --> 01:18:58.670 align:middle line:84%
Because you apply the definition
of delta TC set at scale delta.

01:18:58.670 --> 01:19:00.420 align:middle line:84%
This is something I
should have mentioned.

01:19:00.420 --> 01:19:02.680 align:middle line:84%
I will try to remember
to mention it next time.

01:19:02.680 --> 01:19:05.560 align:middle line:84%
So this set that is
contained actually

01:19:05.560 --> 01:19:08.440 align:middle line:84%
has already size bigger
than the size of A.

01:19:08.440 --> 01:19:11.110 align:middle line:84%
But in addition to having larger
size, it has good spacing.

01:19:11.110 --> 01:19:13.680 align:middle line:90%


01:19:13.680 --> 01:19:15.880 align:middle line:84%
But one question
is that I'm going

01:19:15.880 --> 01:19:18.120 align:middle line:84%
to answer next time
is, How can we be sure

01:19:18.120 --> 01:19:19.460 align:middle line:90%
that something contains?

01:19:19.460 --> 01:19:22.440 align:middle line:84%
So this notion of delta s
is set is bad in the sense

01:19:22.440 --> 01:19:24.600 align:middle line:90%
that it is not monotone.

01:19:24.600 --> 01:19:28.000 align:middle line:84%
So if you take a set
which has this spacing

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:31.450 align:middle line:84%
condition or non-concentration
condition and make it larger,

01:19:31.450 --> 01:19:34.952 align:middle line:84%
you may lose the
non-concentration condition.

01:19:34.952 --> 01:19:35.910 align:middle line:90%
And that's kind of bad.

01:19:35.910 --> 01:19:38.550 align:middle line:84%
So we'll see how to get
around this next time.

01:19:38.550 --> 01:19:41.970 align:middle line:90%


01:19:41.970 --> 01:19:43.970 align:middle line:90%
Any other questions?

01:19:43.970 --> 01:19:44.890 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:19:44.890 --> 01:19:47.090 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I wonder
in the two cases

01:19:47.090 --> 01:19:50.310 align:middle line:84%
you wrote, so in the first
case, we said that it's dense,

01:19:50.310 --> 01:19:51.630 align:middle line:90%
so somehow it is large.

01:19:51.630 --> 01:19:54.630 align:middle line:84%
But in the second case, what's
the intuition behind, OK,

01:19:54.630 --> 01:19:57.630 align:middle line:84%
I have one element that
is far away from the set,

01:19:57.630 --> 01:19:59.610 align:middle line:90%
and then we can get the answer?

01:19:59.610 --> 01:20:02.170 align:middle line:84%
PABLO SHMERKIN: It's
really very similar to what

01:20:02.170 --> 01:20:04.170 align:middle line:84%
